commit_message:
Fix cells capacity calculation for n:1 virt drivers

The capacity calculation in cells assumes a 1:1 mapping for
compute_hosts:nova-compute. Fix this calculation to allow for
drivers that have an n:1 mapping.

Co-Authored-By: John Villalovos <john.l.villalovos@intel.com>
Closes-Bug: 1385468
Change-Id: If361b8bedd81147120581f7f9fe43b8b3f4325e5

commit_message:
VMware: Fix missing target resource pool

The volume is cloned while creating it from another volume, snapshot
or image. Currently, the target resource pool is unset while calling
vCenter CloneVM_Task API.

So when a clone happens across clusters in a vCenter clone fails.
This patch fixes the problem by setting the target resource pool
(returned by datastore selection logic) while invoking clone.

Closes-Bug: #1416456

Change-Id: Ib1023efe6fd19d604af89f7e4b4f67640d778d39
(cherry picked from commit 0df929e60c9053240b792dea7ed7e2c10de69fc1)

commit_message:
Support identity_uri in provider

After https://review.openstack.org/152321 was merged, it was no
longer guaranteed that some now deprecated settings like auth_host
and auth_protocol would be present in glance-api.conf. This breaks
the Glance provider, which expects them to be present.

This patch adds support for identity_uri in provider, while
keeping backwards compatibility.

Change-Id: Ie8a2e45a4afea4828e02af36e64d65e7d4b7557e

Cliff has a stable release, so testing cliff against stable OSC
is pointless.  Stable cliff is already tested against stable OSC.
Plus this test is just broken.

Change-Id: I42c50ea8fd4b185dd1e745d3bdb6695814840e24
'}, {'created': '2015-06-01 19:23:00.000000000', 'message': 'Remove stable cross-test jobs from cliff

Remove the jobs that run the unit tests of cliff against stable OSC and
neutronclient. We rely on the dsvm jobs to run integration tests of
cliff changes, using both OSC and neutronclient for stable branches.

Configure the jobs that run the unit tests of cliff against stable OSC
and neutronclient to only run when patches are submitted to master.

Change-Id: I42c50ea8fd4b185dd1e745d3bdb6695814840e24
'}]
commit_message:
Remove stable cross-test jobs from cliff

Remove the jobs that run the unit tests of cliff against stable OSC and
neutronclient. We rely on the dsvm jobs to run integration tests of
cliff changes, using both OSC and neutronclient for stable branches.

Configure the jobs that run the unit tests of cliff against stable OSC
and neutronclient to only run when patches are submitted to master.

Change-Id: I42c50ea8fd4b185dd1e745d3bdb6695814840e24

commit_message:
Correct docs on format for glance::policy data

Correct the format of the $policies parameter to glance::policy.
That parameter is passed directly to create_resources, so it needs
to be in a format acceptable to that.

Just updating docs here as anyone already using the policy classes
are likely not using the (incorrectly) documented format, anyway.

Change-Id: I80f1f832db124eef3bfd75907e4a2dcb5a5effca
Closes-bug: 1409897

commit_message:
add option to use dd for swapfile creation

fallocate is faster than using dd to create a thick swapfile with
zeros, but it is not supported on all filesystems (specifically ext3).

This commit adds a fallback to using dd if fallocate fails

Closes-Bug: #1458841

Change-Id: Ie4adf625d85f84a0d89a108ef0438622ab763b9d
(cherry picked from commit ccb16763234a13fc204b91943e3d0c197545f2e9)

[{'created': '2014-11-27 20:51:55.000000000', 'message': "Correctly munge glance_image is_public property

glance expects True/False values whereas this type uses Yes/No.

Without this patch, puppet would return the following message with an
existing glance image with is_public attribute already set to 'True'.

puppet-agent[18190]: (/Stage[main]/Site::Controller/Glance_image[raring-server-cloudimg-amd64]/is_public) is_public changed 'True' to 'Yes'

Change-Id: I532e08e6815a8b03f5eb6a9495d886b9855762c8
"}]
commit_message:
Correctly munge glance_image is_public property

glance expects True/False values whereas this type uses Yes/No.

Without this patch, puppet would return the following message with an
existing glance image with is_public attribute already set to 'True'.

puppet-agent[18190]: (/Stage[main]/Site::Controller/Glance_image[raring-server-cloudimg-amd64]/is_public) is_public changed 'True' to 'Yes'

Change-Id: I532e08e6815a8b03f5eb6a9495d886b9855762c8

commit_message:
update openstackclient requirement to 1.0.3

Commit 5e8910931ceb90a52e00b99610f4a6f29576d497 did this for stable/kilo
but not master, and having a higher minimum required version for
stable/kilo than what's required on master is a bit odd, so do the same
on master.

commit_message:
Fixing keystone v3 version use for horizon

The setting for overriding Horizon's OPENSTACK_API_VERSIONS is not
the correct format. The version should be a number, not a string.

so should be 3, not "v3".

Change-Id: I193d21514b196336796eac067417dc2aaec56433
Closes-Bug: #1460190

The 'Docker' format is added to the default list of supported
formats so it can be selected from the list of formats when creating

commit_message:
Add support for Docker image format

The 'Docker' format is added to the default list of supported
formats so it can be selected from the list of formats when creating
or updating an image. When the docker format is selected, the
disk_format and container_format properties are set appropriately.
This also includes changes to the Format column and filter for the
Images table to handle this type.

Closes-Bug: #1455179
Change-Id: Ie705c86d47c0b6035373b9311454748122185988

commit_message:
Add --wait to server delete

This allows the server delete command to wait for the server to be
deleted (obviously).

The wait method is the same model that Tempest uses, i.e. wait for a 404
on server GET (successful deletion), fail if the server went to ERROR
status, or fail if a timeout is reached.  The default timeout of 300
seconds is also what Tempest uses.

Closes-Bug: #1460112

Change-Id: I0e66c400903e82832944d1cad61e7eb30177c3e8

commit_message:
Update the Upstream OpenStack Configuration guide for NFS backup

In kilo, we added NFS backup service for cinder alongside swift, ceph,
and tsm.

This commit updates the configuration guide with information on how to
configure cinder.conf to use the NFS backup service.

Change-Id: I6de56439c90fbe1e549f42314b8c920fd5a6b6f7

commit_message:
Fix get_instance_by_id, catch NotFound appopriately

novaclient will raise a NotFound exception here instead of returning None,
which the rest of the RUG assumes.

Change-Id: I6812bd01bb4a56433bc1c408040470d3711a0005
Closes-bug: #1459445
(cherry picked from commit ceaf3ce53c29c20dea02fba1b9dcead437991d0c)

commit_message: Instance overview renders erroneous markup Under Instance Detail | Overview | Meta | Key Name an unclosed is rendered for an instance launched without an associated key pair. This seems to be reproducible using Django 1.6.1 in local devstack. The issue seems to be that Django's implementation of the add filter has an issue concatenating a string and a function to localize text. Since that fails and returns an empty string which subsequently is added to the closing tag, the closing tag is the only thing that is displayed. This fix saves the localized value to a variable which is then used in the add filter. Closes-Bug: #1423797 Change-Id: I4452ca4a902bbaf19ae5b2bd9bcbe2900069ac3b

commit_message:
NetApp FC driver shims missing manage/unmanage

The NetApp FC drivers' passthrough shim layers are missing the
manage/unmanage methods, causing the manage/unmanage functions
to fail.  The necessary functionality is already present in
the underlying library layer, so the trivial fix is to add the
functions to the passthrough layers. This patch also adds a
unit test to ensure the four block storage driver interfaces
remain in sync.

Change-Id: I0fa7e16b23e5148f82a8b51bf4380f4384c35759
Closes-Bug: #1444517

- Using the python swift client directly to upload logs
- Using a stand alone python script which is called from our bash
  scripts to upload images.

We need to consolidate these two so we have a common place for our
swift integration code which supports the following

- Upload objects to swift in chunks.

  constraint.

- Deleting objects

commit_message:
Swift client wrapper

We currently upload logs and images to swift in two ways.
- Using the python swift client directly to upload logs
- Using a stand alone python script which is called from our bash
  scripts to upload images.

We need to consolidate these two so we have a common place for our
swift integration code which supports the following

- Upload and download objects.
- Check object size to make sure we are under the 5GB swift
  constraint.
- Retry logic
- Delete objects

I'm also changing the swift client code to always create a
non cached client. This is required for our upload\download
retry mechanism to work properly.

Change-Id: I9993d0b74197a517920468b7fd07e29bbc305ed0
Closes-bug: 1456807

'}, {'created': '2015-05-22 16:23:31.000000000', 'message': "Fixing concurrency bug in heat deployer

Problem:
We want to ensure that only one assembly is in a READY state
for an app. This is to ensure that Solum does not keep around
more heat stacks than are necessary. If there are more than one
assemblies then there are that many number of heat stacks,
which we want to avoid.

So the solution that we came up with is to delete other
READY assemblies when a new assembly has become READY.

However, this solution as is currently implemented
has concurrency issues in the situation when there are multiple
deployers in the system. In our testing we have seen both of
the following:
(a) when two assembly create are triggered in quick succession both
    are deleted
(b) when two assembly creates are triggered in quick succession
    none is deleted

This patch fixes the concurrency issue to ensure that both the
above situations don't arise.

The fix for (a) is to use the 'created_at' timestamp when deleting
assemblies. The idea is to delete all the READY assemblies which
have created_at timestamp which is smaller than the newly created
assemblies' timestamp. The reason this is correct is because there
will be only one READY assembly which will have the highest created_at
timestamp (because we are using a single database). So this assembly
will end up deleting other assemblies which are READY and have a
smaller created_at timestamp.

The fix for (b) is to perform the database writes to update an
assembly's status in a synchronous manner in the deployer itself.
Current code performs this update in an asynchronous manner via the
conductor. In a multiple deployer scenario this asynchronicity causes
race conditions which leads to situations like (b).

Closes-Bug: #1457200
Change-Id: I3482399fb08ebe19870f6dae69e2edc2a0c07685

commit_message:
Fixing concurrency bug in heat deployer

Problem:
We want to ensure that only one assembly is in a READY state
for an app. This is to ensure that Solum does not keep around
more heat stacks than are necessary. If there are more than one
assemblies then there are that many number of heat stacks,
which we want to avoid.

So the solution that we came up with is to delete other
READY assemblies when a new assembly has become READY.

However, this solution as is currently implemented
has concurrency issues in the situation when there are multiple
deployers in the system. In our testing we have seen both of
the following:
(a) when two assembly create are triggered in quick succession both
    are deleted
(b) when two assembly creates are triggered in quick succession
    none is deleted

This patch fixes the concurrency issue to ensure that both the
above situations don't arise.

The fix for (a) is to use the 'created_at' timestamp when deleting
assemblies. The idea is to delete all the READY assemblies which
have created_at timestamp which is smaller than the newly created
assemblies' timestamp. The reason this is correct is because there
will be only one READY assembly which will have the highest created_at
timestamp (because we are using a single database). So this assembly
will end up deleting other assemblies which are READY and have a
smaller (more recent) created_at timestamp.

The fix for (b) is to perform the database writes to update an
assembly's status in a synchronous manner in the deployer itself.
Current code performs this update in an asynchronous manner via the
conductor. In a multiple deployer scenario this asynchronicity causes
race conditions which leads to situations like (b).

Closes-Bug: #1457200
Change-Id: I3482399fb08ebe19870f6dae69e2edc2a0c07685

[{'created': '2015-03-30 16:11:38.000000000', 'message': 'Fix date pickers in metering modal

commit_message:
Fix date pickers in metering modal

The metering forms were using the date picker functionality from the
d3 line chart library, this used to work when it was loaded as a whole
page as the d3 libary would run intending to setup any d3 graphs however
now it is being loaded as a modal the elements that would be affected by
the d3 code do not exist at page load time.

In order to get the date picker events to be added to the elements on
the form when the modal loads, the JS in the forms template has been
extended in this patch to support adding those events.

This patch also changes the data attributes on the form elements so that
they do not conflict with any d3 line chart elements.

Alongside the javascript this patch fixes bug to do with parsing the
dates in metering utils and adds UTs to prevent regression.

Change-Id: I4e239daa03b2f54e434254bac48ba0cceb037b5d
Closes-Bug: 1427756

commit_message:
Verbose waiting for status in neutron FWaaS

In case that neutron doesn't reach desired status, exception is raised.
Curently there is missing more info about current status, that is not
matching.

Change-Id: I3aaeee8615550fdd0a14c57a5475af94f765641b

commit_message:
Fix server creation n test_large_ops

The test_large_ops test creates multiple servers directly via
servers_client instead of the manager (which doesn't handle multi
server creation too well). However it failed to pass proper network
configuration to servers_client.

Change-Id: I65414880b41473690bf5e9edae9fd273409acf5d

commit_message:
Log info for Fernet tokens over 255 chars

Fernet tokens were designed to be short and maintain some of the usability of
UUID-like tokens by being copy-pastable. Depending on the deployment
configuration, we could still generate tokens that are over 255 characters. If
this is the case, we should log some information.

Change-Id: I3aa52f7e09c4cf717ddd28d14ee36b80f53b012b

commit_message:
Set gw external net to empty for multi-provider networks

Today the gateway_external_network_id variable is not
set when provider networks are configured. Both the
external_network_id and the gateway_external_network
should be set to empty strings for the provider network
to work with a single l3 agent for multiple external
networks.

Closes-Bug: #1410951

Change-Id: Iaf5547a6ff18818e05f97cdf9d24f2c70737568c

commit_message:
Add Configuration option to configure delete namespaces

With the introduction for distributed virtual routers
the existence of namespaces in the nodes have increased
tremendously and so the namespace should be cleaned up
whenever required.

So let us provide a configurable option to configure in
the local.conf to either enable or disable the
router_delete_namespaces option for neutron.

This patch introduces "Q_DEL_NAMESPACE" which will be
used to populate the "router_delete_namespaces".

Change-Id: Ie74156a802ca9c383364b65f8b68b4c8feaa1fea
Closes-Bug: #1413777

[{'created': '2014-11-17 22:31:18.000000000', 'message': 'Add coverage-package-name to tox.ini for coverage

Recent pbrs support a coverage-package-name argument which allows you to
explicitly specify the package name to test coverage of. By default it
takes the project name (python-openstacksdk) and splits the "python-"
prefix off, leaving it to check coverage of the nonexistent
"openstacksdk" package. After this, "tox -e cover html" works and drops
the results in a cover/ folder under root.

Change-Id: I55e3fb274158aa37938329f2153c5c9597e64915
'}]
commit_message:
Add coverage-package-name to tox.ini for coverage

Recent pbrs support a coverage-package-name argument which allows you to
explicitly specify the package name to test coverage of. By default it
takes the project name (python-openstacksdk) and splits the "python-"
prefix off, leaving it to check coverage of the nonexistent
"openstacksdk" package. After this, "tox -e cover html" works and drops
the results in a cover/ folder under root.

Change-Id: I55e3fb274158aa37938329f2153c5c9597e64915

commit_message:
Enable trove plugin for trove tempest job

Trove will no longer be tested in the devstack updown job because
its configuration has moved from the devstack repo to the trove
repo, so remove the no-longer-necessary enable_trove flag in that
job.

Also remove the flag from the tempest job but replace it with the
configuration option to enable the plugin so that job does not
functionally change.

Change-Id: Iac738fb6071c8cb60961872cdef371582041d0a2
Depends-On: I8f9f1a015edb7ec1033e2eaf0b29ab15d89384ce

commit_message:
Create instance_extra entry if it doesn't update

When updating an instance, if there is no instance_extra, for older
instances, we make sure we create one if there is not one already.

This keeps flavor data migrations (ie system_metadata ->
instance_extra) from failing when the system_metadata entries are soft
deleted but an instance_extra entry is not created because it was
"updated" assuming an instance_extra entry already existed, leaving
the instance with no flavor data.

Closes-Bug: #1459758
Change-Id: I715217d98729c6c5ac45d64d8bacaaca745ff3d7
(cherry picked from commit e776d6fddf047ff5dc77420263bd60756ba6a988)

commit_message:
Fix xag param in read call from instance_disk_iter

Live testing revealed a bug in
nova_powervm.virt.powervm.disk.driver.DiskAdapter.instance_disk_iter
whereby Adapter.read's xag parameter was a single xag rather than a
list.  Fixed the bug and added UTs.

Change-Id: I9f0d78129fca97dacbea3bcbbdda25763850804e

commit_message:
Improve Endpoint Configurability

This change modifies the available endpoint configuration options to
allow for greater flexibility in configuring endpoint URIs. This is part
of a larger set of changes (outlined in 1274979), which seek to
normalize the endpoint options.

Change-Id: I5154974adc83df1f8799baa4c2863c1481ae74ea
Partial-Bug: 1274979

Technically speaking, I wrote an inline review. Please don't try to fix Puppet4 issues in this patch.

Also please consider my remarks here:

* when you enter in a community, please try to avoid this kind of comments that can be considered unfriendly. We are a group of people who work together and try to move forward on the same problematic in a productive way. I would like to avoid this kind of situation in the future.
* you have to read/sign/respect the CLA which is the DNA of our OpenStack community and moreover Open-Source in general. There is no debate around this and we all agree about the rules. I would suggest to discuss with Mathieu and probably use the "Co-Authored-By" in the commit message.

-1 for now because of my inline review, I'll drop it when my comments will be addressed and also when Mathieu & Colleen will drop their -2.

Thanks'}, {'account_id': 14496, 'date': '2015-05-29 16:13:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I will address your technical concerns in short order. With regard to your remarks:

* The intent wasn't unfriendly, it was an attempt at humor. I've already addressed this by offering an unqualified apology to Mathieu for my incorrect assumption as to how this was to be received. He rejected this apology.

* I absolutely agree regarding the importance of the CLA, Code of Conduct, et. al. That being said, I reject that I violated the CLA in practice or in spirit. Up until this point, no violation has been articulated to my satisfaction. Failed humor does not equal disrespect, nor does disagreement.

* I've already offered to credit Mathieu via a 'Co-Authored-By' field, despite the fact that none of his 'prior art' exists in the patch anymore,  but he has yet to respond favorably."}, {'account_id': 14496, 'date': '2015-05-29 16:20:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 14496, 'date': '2015-05-29 17:17:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-29 18:34:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Mathieu,

After taking some time to reflect on this issue and solicit feedback
from various community and foundation members whose opinions I respect, it has become clear to me that it was primarily my response to this issue which has allowed it to snowball and become an unnecessary and inappropriate distraction for the community. We all want to ship code and improve the modules, and this has detracted from our ability to do that.

My earlier apology for my inappropriate attempt at humor still stands,
but I would also like to apologize for my dismissive attitude towards
your concerns. It has become obvious in subsequent discussions that
there are differences in opinion (there are as many opinions as people
I've talked to) on what constitutes appropriate attribution, and at what
point that becomes appropriate, but that is *completely separate* from
demonstrating basic respect to our peers, which was lacking on my part in this instance. 

I am sorry. 

I hope we can move past this for not only our own benefit, but the benefit of the community.

In practical terms, I would like to propose the following options:

* I will add a 'co-authored-by' tag to each patch I land to address the
issues outlined in bug #1274979[0]. I intended to land patches to fix
the issue for all 9 remaining affected modules, so I would add that tag
for each of those.

* I will abandon the two existing patches I've landed (in puppet-nova
and puppet-swift), as well as abstain from landing patches related to
bug #1274979[0], leaving those to be fixed by either yourself or someone else in the community.

Separately from whichever of these two options seems most appropriate to you, I want to kick off a conversation with members of the community and the foundation to create better guidance on what constitutes appropriate attribution and hopefully establish some quantitive guidelines on attribution which can be fed back in the community to ensure that everyone is on the same page. I think we can all agree that it is important everyone feels respected and valued for the work they've done. This is my attempt to make sure that your original concern gets addressed (because that is important) without actually blocking any progress within the modules.

Please let me know which of the above two options works for you. I hope we can move past this incident and work together going forward.

Best Regards,

Richard Raseley

[0] - https://bugs.launchpad.net/puppet-nova/+bug/1274979"}, {'account_id': 7156, 'date': '2015-06-01 17:46:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: -Code-Review

Richard Raseley:

I greatly appreciate your response and accept your apologies without reserve. I hope we can now move on to new things and work together to improve the project and community.

As for the next step to move forward, I would like everybody to be able to work without exclusion, this includes you.

A lot of changes were abandoned in the past related to this bug because people didn't agree with my implementation and which David Moreau Simard (a coworker) used as well for puppet-swift: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/topic:bug/1274979,n,z

I suggest we restore them all and continue applying changes to them. Anyone can fetch the change, apply new change and resubmit them as long as he has the permission (just for the sake of being polite and respectful) of the original change's owner which I hereby grant to anyone that wishes to work on them.

This will have the benefit of keeping the implementation history and original authorship. Anyone working on those changes can add its name on it (using the Co-authored-by tag) as he is also entitled to recognition for the work done.

Let me know if this is an acceptable solution."}, {'account_id': 287, 'date': '2015-06-01 17:58:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Glad to see this issue going towards an amicable resolution.

It's probably worth reminding that to pull a patch from someone else's changeset, one can simply use `git review -d $NUMBER_OF_THE_CHANGESET`"}, {'account_id': 14496, 'date': '2015-06-01 18:09:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

* The specific implementation we go with is a different discussion, which we'll be ready to have once we get all the 'house cleaning' complete."}, {'account_id': 14496, 'date': '2015-06-01 18:10:19.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

commit_message:
Improve Endpoint Configurability

This change modifies the available endpoint configuration options to
allow for greater flexibility in configuring endpoint URIs. This is part
of a larger set of changes (outlined in 1274979), which seek to
normalize the endpoint options.

Change-Id: I8039a092e4f74a454f0e80f0978b07c59226a479
Partial-Bug: 1274979

commit_message:
Fix condition in _publish_and_retry_on_missing_exchange()

The current condition logic in _publish_and_retry_on_missing_exchange()
replaces passed `timeout` value with `rpc_response_timeout` config value.

This patch fix it.

Change-Id: I451cd2b5da78a3d7011466dfb14669aa1dcf1d5c

commit_message:
Compare each chunk of large objects when downloading

This allows the use of --skip-identical when downloading SLOs and DLOs,
while still only requiring one request for normal objects.

Change-Id: I237ec5a8cc4d1119b6d3f166db81a977a50a4e4e
Related-Bug: #1379252

commit_message:
Split admin volumes tests to it's own test file

Currently volumes tests is in admin/volumes/tests.py, it
should have it's own test file like snapshots and volume_types.

Change-Id: Ic39397bff25626893b5a2c218837d2b3525f7526
Closes-Bug: #1459904

@David, I'm in the process of absorbing your points.

Bower is kind of neither here nor there with regards to the patch.  We can refer directly to the xstatic libs for all the dependencies, that's not really a blocker.  We could, for example, remove Bower and keep the package.json, which speaks specifically to Karma.

Karma has been astoundingly useful for developing the thousands of lines of tests, which bring our code coverage in total, if committed, well into the 80%s.  Without it we couldn't have narrowed down the branch coverage, which is above 70%.  So in the process of developing tests we've found Karma to be invaluable, but understand Bower is not really a prereq for that.

Thanks!  Looking forward to working with everyone to make a great developer environment."}, {'account_id': 14307, 'date': '2015-05-01 23:36:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 53.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-02 00:58:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 53: Verified-1

@RobCresswell : I tend to agree.  HOWEVER, that's a discussion that should happen as a tuning patch, and shouldn't interfere with getting this patch merged.

I only point this out because that type of thing has been happening from all sides on this patch.  Examples:  Making it dependent upon an I18n patch which will be merged at a much later date.  Why would a testing patch be dependent upon I18n and not vice-versa?

So, I'd really like to get this patch merged, and then work out the tuning minutiae."}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-06-01 15:56:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 74:

Hey Rob...thanks for the review!

I'd rather just run PhantomJS for now.  Right now the unit tests are here to validate things at a unit level, and though that can change by browser, we have to weigh that against what is available on any given system.  We cannot assume that people can or even should have Chrome/Chromium or Firefox on their system, and in this content we certainly cannot test IE.  (That would be more suited to Selenium tests with remote Windows systems, etc.)  So I'd run with PhantomJS for now.

I think this patch is ready for approval, albeit with changes as suggested by many.  Relying on the i18n patch will significantly delay this patch, if for no other reason than there is still contention about the i18n patch.  This patch addresses those issues simply and can be fixed once the i18n patch comes through.

Thanks everybody for the comments...let's get this through so we can finish our testing!"}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-06-01 15:58:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 74:

As another note, individuals (or the gate) can easily configure the testing on various browsers, but for everyday use, PhantomJS is going to be much more accessible to all, and more useful.'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-06-01 16:01:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 74: Code-Review+2

I think this is ready to go in.  I do agree some additional tweaks and best practices can be established moving forward (like adding more browsers), but I think this is far enough along to build on.  I just tested it successfully on Ubuntu 14.04 with:

./run_tests.sh -k

./run_tests.sh --karma

./run_tests.sh (just to make sure there is no interference)

./run_tests.sh -j (just to make sure there is no interference)

./run_tests.sh -s (just to make sure there is no interference)

./run_tests.sh --runserver 0.0.0.0:8005  then checking Jasmine'}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-06-01 16:15:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 74:

commit_message:
Get unit tests working with Karma

Establish features for running Karma tests.  Separate karma configurations
are used due to current overlap of template file structure.

You can run the karma tests via:
  ./run_tests.sh --karma

The Karma framework allows for many features like unit test coverage and
provides a common configuration for different test runners.

Change-Id: I79680ef6369383c148da68e6677945886a48df81
Implements: blueprint karma

commit_message:
Remove deprecated pxe_deploy_{kernel, ramdisk}

In the last cycle we have renamed some parameters to make it more
consistent across different drivers. This patch is removing the deprecated
pxe_deploy_{kernel, ramdisk} parameters from the code and updating the
documentation accordingly.

Depends-On: I3dcf8df130efc0c2ea35695018bedba31bf0570c
Change-Id: I07eb7ad28929b651cf04ef3955903e4f4ecf9900

command but the command makes output only if there is a bridge present

Closes-Bug: 1447191

commit_message:
Create bridges in ovsdb monitor functional tests

The test waits inside for output from 'ovsdb-client monitor Bridge'
command but the command makes output only if there is a bridge present
in ovsdb. This patch adds an OVSBridgeFixture to setup so every test
case has a bridge for sure.

Change-Id: I40e1c99ec956c92fa1c7763eb98f7f2ce6fcd226
Closes-Bug: 1447191

commit_message:
Add updating jobs statuses before cluster deletion

We need to update statuses of jobs of current cluster before
deletion. This patch will allow to mark success in Sahara
already success jobs in Oozie.

Change-Id: If504a459e9d39031a7de0f20ea91124f6eed1253
Closes-bug: 1459226

commit_message:
Limit router gw ports' stateful fixed IPs to one per address family

Validate a router's gateway port during a router update by ensuring
it has no more than one v4 fixed IP and one v6 (statefully-assigned)
fixed IP.

Note that there is no limit on v6 addresses from SLAAC and
DHCPv6-stateless subnets as they are automatically allocated.

Change-Id: I6a328048b99af39ab9497fd9f265d1a9b95b7148
Closes-Bug: 1438819
Partially-implements: blueprint multiple-ipv6-prefixes
(cherry picked from commit 1bfd86e1ef7148370798aa99c868d7f931fcbf78)

commit_message:
Use accessors instead of private attributes for Ml2 plugin

Start using accessors instead of private attributes of PortContext
and NetworkContext where it is possible.

Closes-bug: #1424587

Change-Id: Ie3d963ae6cee9782d65ba683936072602c78ebaa

commit_message:
OVS-agent: Remove optional flags from br_tun.deferred() method

Currently they have no users.
They are not appropriate for this higher-level interface anyway.

Change-Id: I76b8d718e714728df88685ec41262958d2e78cb9

commit_message:
Ensure metadata network works with DVR

As DVR routers use a different type of interface, this patch
amends the DHCP agent code ensuring that a metadata proxy is
spawned when the metadata network feature is enabled on the
DHCP agent.

(Cherry-picked from ec408ac379108eee26d87a8d9834180db11877e0)

Change-Id: Id7f2e891c0753620a604cf6160c6b592db1aa284
Closes-Bug: #1447344

commit_message:
Add handler flushing to roles that need it

This patch adds handler flushing as the last task in each role to ensure
that there are log files present when the rsyslog client configuration
task is executed a little later in the playbook that consumes the role.

Closes-Bug: #1458822
Change-Id: I92a26b620aa7bc0fbe33175594d37da7d5aca7df
(cherry picked from commit c7951c43e2f3bae01c595151af33d35dcf0b3ca4)

[{'created': '2015-05-14 07:43:15.000000000', 'message': 'Support multiple IPv6 prefixes on internal router ports for an HA Router

As part of BP multiple IPv6 prefixes, we can have multiple IPv6 prefixes on
router internal ports. Patch, I7d4e8194815e626f1cfa267f77a3f2475fdfa3d1, adds
the necessary support for a legacy router.

For an HA router, instead of configuring the addresses on the router internal
ports we should be updating the keepalived config file and let keepalived
configure the addresses depending on the state of the router.

Following are the observations with the current code for an HA router.
1. IPv6 addresses are configured on the router internal ports (i.e., qr-xxx)
   irrespective of the state of the router. As the same IP is configured on multiple
   ports you will notice dadfailed status on the ports.
2. Keepalived configuration is not updated with the new IPv6 addresses.

This patch addresses the above issues for an HA Router.

Closes-Bug: #1446161
Partially-implements: blueprint multiple-ipv6-prefixes
Change-Id: Icb9a0e4e6e5deafbdc0135ce7e6b100b1725df66
(cherry picked from commit 99de7cdf700218a54fa6fc2e194cca3ccb35abd4)

commit_message:
Support multiple IPv6 prefixes on internal router ports for an HA Router

As part of BP multiple IPv6 prefixes, we can have multiple IPv6 prefixes on
router internal ports. Patch, I7d4e8194815e626f1cfa267f77a3f2475fdfa3d1, adds
the necessary support for a legacy router.

For an HA router, instead of configuring the addresses on the router internal
ports we should be updating the keepalived config file and let keepalived
configure the addresses depending on the state of the router.

Following are the observations with the current code for an HA router.
1. IPv6 addresses are configured on the router internal ports (i.e., qr-xxx)
   irrespective of the state of the router. As the same IP is configured on multiple
   ports you will notice dadfailed status on the ports.
2. Keepalived configuration is not updated with the new IPv6 addresses.

This patch addresses the above issues for an HA Router.

Closes-Bug: #1446161
Partially-implements: blueprint multiple-ipv6-prefixes
Change-Id: Icb9a0e4e6e5deafbdc0135ce7e6b100b1725df66
(cherry picked from commit 99de7cdf700218a54fa6fc2e194cca3ccb35abd4)

commit_message:
Eventlet green threads not released back to pool

Presently, the wsgi server allows persist connections hence even after
the response is sent to the client, it doesn't close the client socket
connection.
Because of this problem, the green thread is not released back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the
response is sent and read successfully by the client, you simply have to
set keepalive to False when you create a wsgi server.

Icehouse backport note: socket_timeout was dropped, it was introduced
in 0.14[*] and Icehouse eventlet lower bound is 0.13

[*] https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/commit/7d4916f01462de09cb58853d9de2e85777c2ad5b

Note: The required unit-tests are manually added to the below path,
as new path for unit-tests is not present in stable/icehouse release.
nova/tests/test_wsgi.py

DocImpact:
Added wsgi_keep_alive option (default=True).

SecurityImpact

Conflicts:
        nova/tests/unit/test_wsgi.py

Closes-Bug: #1361360
(cherry picked from commit 04d7a724fdf80db51e73f12c5b8c982db9310742)

Change-Id: I3b14a37edbe4bdc5db31ff4f08f78e78b60077ff

commit_message:
Add simplegeneric to requirements

simplegeneric is supposed to be installed by WSME, but for some reasons
it was missed in py3 env.

This caused the openstack/ironic gate to block.  A hack was put into
place adding it to tox.ini.  Add it to global-requirements.txt so that
the hack can be removed.

Change-Id: I34dcb7f56c43bf7310d49d052f6ac868f7401296

commit_message:
Migrate to oslo.serialization

This removes akanda.rug's usage of openstack.common.jsonutils
and instead uses the equivalent oslo_serialiation.jsonutils.

Note the old module is still left in place as its used by other old
oslo-incubator things.

Change-Id: I94c3d0433180120fc55328ae9ae6917af518ffc9

commit_message:
Add vmware-nsx repo to Neutron

According to procedure defined in [1], this patch proposes Neutron
to embrace vmware-nsx within its fold. This project provides networking
support for the NSX family.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/doc/source/devref/sub_projects.rst

Change-Id: I7f3a52d255b48fc14452d7fd37c20bee7e413efe

commit_message:
Fix get_instance_by_id, catch NotFound appopriately

novaclient will raise a NotFound exception here instead of returning None,
which the rest of the RUG assumes.

Change-Id: I6812bd01bb4a56433bc1c408040470d3711a0005
Closes-bug: #1459445

Add debug-user element

New patchset patch-id matches previous patchset, but commit message has changed.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-04-11 18:37:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

First time reviewer on specs, long time documenter of API.

I'm concerned about confusion between task and state. 

Also consider billing.

Also asking if there are two POSTs  you're proposing. 

Other comments inline."}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-04-11 18:37:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Arg gerrit ate my inline comments. Why gerrit why?

I sense we could enhance the documentation for states as well, there are plenty of questions about it.
What about shelving a server? Is that a potential use case here? Shelving a server would mean you could leave it suspended without being billed, for example.
Edit
Line 33:	
I've discussed some below as well, but I sense there could be user confusion between tasks and states. What if a paused server is in error? Will the customer get billed?
Edit
Line 40:	
Would POST to /v3/servers/
do something different from POST /v3/servers/<uuid>?
Is one a listing of all servers tasks and the other tasks for a single server?
Can a server have more than one task assigned?
Edit
Line 45:	
I suspect you'll get confusion between the state and task. These are the states: pause unpause suspend resume lock unlock
and so on. What will be the differentiator between task and state?
Edit
Line 68:	
Why would you want to do this? Give your dev perspective as well as a user need.
Edit
Line 76:	
This sounds like a doc problem more than a design problem?
Edit
Line 132:	
Would users want to be notified on the progress with last_updated?
Edit
Line 198:	
Be more explicit: -Reference documentation in WADL for POST /v3/servers/ and POST /v3/servers/<uuid> with JSON requests and response examples as well as definitions for each task. (bare minimum)
How-to information with curl commands for using this extension (nice to have)
Do you expect that policies for the use of this will also need to be documented?"}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2014-04-11 19:52:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Going to try my best to respond without the comments being inline.

Something I may need to make more clear is that this addition is just about exposing more information, it doesn't change anything else within Nova.  The goal of this initial work is to take the task_state of an instance and enhance it and expose it as its own entity.  This sets up future work to improve things.  But if a paused server in ERROR is currently billed that will not change, nor the opposite if that's true.

Line 40: I will clarify this a bit, but basically the POST to /v3/servers is meant to indicate a server create and /v3/servers/<uuid> which would really be /v3/servers/<uuid>/action is any other action like reboot/pause/rescue/rebuild/etc...
A server can not have more than one task assigned because the current task_state checking keeps that from happening.  This is something that could potentially change for specific actions in the future, but isn't being touched now.

Line 45:  Roughly you can consider the old task_states to be the new 'task' and 'state' refers to it's status.  So task will be the action taking place on an instance, and state will be the status of that action.  I almost went with 'status' instead but I tend to think of a task being in a state rather than having a status.  Would it help to clarify if I had some more examples?  task would be spawning|resize|reboot|pause|rescue|etc.. and state would be active|error|complete.

Line 68: There's no user need for this.  From a dev perspective my thinking is that as we call various methods in Nova they are more likely to want to update the task state or progress than the instance itself.  I have a general feeling that we update task_state more than we update an instance in other ways, but haven't researched this enough to be sure.  I'm not sure if it makes more sense to clarify this point or just remove it.  But it's an implicit assumption I'm making while thinking of tasks so I wanted to enumerate it in case it helps explain other decisions I've made.

Line 76: I wouldn't classify it as a docs problem, though docs would help with the visibility.  It is somewhat of a design problem since instance-actions are constrained to a single one per request while tasks are not.  Which I now realize I didn't mention because it's out of scope for now, but there could be multiple tasks created for a single request.

Line 132: Users can poll for progress by checking last_updated, but no new notifications will be sent.  Future work may add new notifications around this but I'm focusing on API visibility at this point and trying not to change any other part of Nova in order to keep the complexity down.

Line 198: The POSTs won't change at all from what they are currently.  And the jsonschema definition in the blueprint is intended to be representative of the return for all posts to /v3/servers or /v3/servers/<uuid>/action.  At least as representative as I can be without having implemented this and seeing if some changes make sense.  I can handcraft WADL definitions for each response if necessary but I would think it would be better to get that from the implementation since it's possible for small changes to emerge from the review and implementation process.
curl commands are no different than the current curl commands for creating a server or performing an action on it.
And policies will not be affected either."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-11 20:07:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Initial version of Heat datasource driver

This patch is about a WIP version of Heat datasource driver. Only
stacks, resources and events are included.  Still trying to figure out
how Congress build data models among tables.

commit_message:
project create is missing --parent in doc

'project create' is missing '--parent <project>' argument in doc,
actually it is supported.

Change-Id: Id0edaab4e2b02a1f7d974d71a11c7c373e31806f
Closes-Bug: #1460256

commit_message:
Introduce an experimental job for Linux Bridge

The Linux Bridge ML2 driver for Neutron needs to be tested
to ensure that changes to Neutron do not break this mechanism driver.
Operators that are not interested in SDN solutions but still interested
in using Neutron will want to use the Linux Bridge driver for their
deployments, so we should test it.

Change-Id: Iccba951301d2c09e01b6c1a15ed1e88c8e0db69e

I'd very much like to see this go in before release.  Though, I can't say that it is release critical, it is a significant wart on a brand new feature for Neutron.

Coupled with a bug in the python-neutronclient (same bug #) which passes IPv4 as a default even with an IPv6 pool it allows creating an unusable subnet which is marked as IPv4 but has IPv6 addresses.  This fix is very low risk as it very carefully raises an error in the specific case that should not be allowed, other code paths still work and are tested fully with tempest tests."}, {'account_id': 14258, 'date': '2015-04-27 18:55:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-04-30 18:04:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

commit_message:
Enable notification about external mirror utilities in terminal

This patch enables displaying of MOTD banner in ssh and adds
short notification about external mirror utilities
(fuel-createmirror and fuel-package-updates) to /etc/motd.

Change-Id: I292cbac9d785af801282664ee59264fd69c22ca0
Partial-Bug: #1455048

[{'created': '2015-05-29 21:43:10.000000000', 'message': 'Pass locale environment variables through tox

On Python 3, when there are no locale environment settings, the default
encoding is ASCII. This causes the unicode in the README.rst for rfc3986
to trigger an UnicodeDecodeError exception.

Closes-bug: 1460206
Change-Id: If05e3fe76450c06431413f63e46e154cf44fc1cf
'}, {'created': '2015-05-29 22:19:49.000000000', 'message': 'Pass locale environment variables through tox

On Python 3, when there are no locale environment settings, the default

commit_message:
Force the value of LC_ALL to be en_US.UTF-8

On Python 3, if LC_ALL is not passed then the interpreter will assume it
is C (which causes the interpreter to use ASCII). This, in turn, causes
the unicode in the README.rst for rfc3986 to trigger a UnicodeDecodeError
exception.

jlvillal (John Villalovos) pointed out
I340c88ea7d098ca5943d60adc73f63a0af79a405 in IRC as the fix to this bug.

Closes-bug: 1460206
Change-Id: If05e3fe76450c06431413f63e46e154cf44fc1cf

commit_message:
Neutron QoS API Extension

This specification defines a basic QoS implementation
providing ratelimiting, which could be easily extended
in the future.

Co-Authored-By: Miguel Angel Ajo <mangelajo@redhat.com>

Change-Id: I3e2bc9a37879874ca21eb7efd0832894dc860892

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code

commit_message:
Removed non-free color profile from .jpg

All the .jpg files in doc/source/essays had this embedded:
"Copyright 2007 Apple Inc., all rights reserved."

This is an ICC color profile which is copyrighted by Apple
and which is non-free, and may trigger some warnings/errors
by the distribution linters.

This patch converts the .jpg into the sRGB color space. I
did this simply loading the images in GIMP, and exporting
again after accepting the auto-coversion to sRGB.

Change-Id: Ibfdf0828ff149d5c83eb864c4fb854e80868a613

commit_message:
Fix config file generation

After commit 4154ce7578de5cedf41b130e9026710e5d393422, it is no
longer possible to generate heat.conf because
heat.openstack.common.policy was still listed in
config-generator.conf

Swift recon introduced a new key for storage policies, and the CLI expected this
key in the server response. However, if one updates the CLI but not yet the
server an exception will be raised, because there is no default value and no
check if the key is included in the response.

This change checks if the policies key is included in the response and updates

Change-Id: I7c7a90f9933bec2ab45595df9dc600a6cba65666
'}]
commit_message:
Make swift-recon compatible for servers without storage policies

Swift recon introduced a new key for storage policies, and the CLI expected this
key in the server response. However, if one updates the CLI but not yet the
server an exception will be raised, because there is no default value and no
check if the key is included in the response.

This change checks if the policies key is included in the response and updates
one test to ensure backward compability.

Closes-Bug: 1453599

Change-Id: I7c7a90f9933bec2ab45595df9dc600a6cba65666

commit_message:
Change logic of wait_for_ping

If host is not pingable, TimeoutException will be raisen with unreadable
message. This patch fixes such situation.

Closes-Bug: #1454381
Change-Id: If10e27a77f79b59c162b7e6148eecf234c0160a7

[{'created': '2015-05-12 19:54:09.000000000', 'message': "Update build hooks.

The pbr setup_hook has not been needed for a while, so remove it.  The
neutron hook has been broken for a while: it places a setup_requires
build dependency on everything in neutron/__init__.py, which is
non-empty, but setup_requires is handled by easy install so we try
very hard to avoid it. Instead, we can use environment markers to
selectively include the win32 dependencies without requiring that
neutron be importable during setup.py execution. This is unusual
in OpenStack and will eventually be moved to a regular
requirements.txt dependency with the same marker - once we've finished
the integration work to make markers work properly in
requirements.txt.

Change-Id: Icdc403a3ccf06daeccf2a907a7bfeafd8dbbb5dd
"}]
commit_message:
Update build hooks.

The pbr setup_hook has not been needed for a while, so remove it.  The
neutron hook has been broken for a while: it places a setup_requires
build dependency on everything in neutron/__init__.py, which is
non-empty, but setup_requires is handled by easy install so we try
very hard to avoid it. Instead, we can use environment markers to
selectively include the win32 dependencies without requiring that
neutron be importable during setup.py execution. This is unusual
in OpenStack and will eventually be moved to a regular
requirements.txt dependency with the same marker - once we've finished
the integration work to make markers work properly in
requirements.txt.

Change-Id: Icdc403a3ccf06daeccf2a907a7bfeafd8dbbb5dd

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

@Carl Baldwin, when lease information (the expiration time) is stored in neutron DB, use --dhcp-script can write the saved to lease to stdout when dnsmasq startup. However, since the implementation for bug-1202392 (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/37580/) dhcp lease info is not maintained in neutron DB any more. So we don't have lease information saved, and so cannot write it when dnsmasq startup.

Now this fix is to store the lease to disk file. Forgive me if I'm missing something, but why are we pulling the info in from the neutron DB, writing it out to the hosts file and then triggering a script to make dnsmasq call the class again to read that hosts file info back in all to finally write out the leases file?

Wouldn't it be far fewer ops (and less complexity since we wouldn't need the external script) to just have it read in _iter_hosts like we do in _output_hosts_file and do the ops all in the same pass?"}, {'account_id': 11762, 'date': '2015-01-06 12:43:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Kevin, we are not writing any lease file.'}, {'account_id': 11762, 'date': '2015-01-06 13:42:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

@Brian, thanks for your comments, but I am trying to understand the problem you encountered. Could you share any error logs?

I didn't use dev-stack but used pip-install to setup and verify in my test env. I will try dev-stack tomorrow to recreate the problem you faced."}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-01-06 14:31:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Han

The problem I was seeing was that the script wasn't getting copied over to /usr/local/bin, so the dhcp agent kept logging that it couldn't be run.  Sorry, I don't have the exact string but will try and reproduce it on another system today (the old one got *really* broken when I ran 'python setup.py develop' for some reason).

Either way, the reason I noted that extra entry in setup.cfg was that the old lease-update script had one - run 'git log -p setup.cfg' to see what I mean.  I didn't know if that was causing the problem or not, but seemed like it was missing.  I'm still trying to figure that out myself as well."}, {'account_id': 161, 'date': '2015-01-06 22:31:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Han: Ah, I see, I saw the print and misinterpreted what was happening :-) This is why I shouldn't code review sick :-D"}, {'account_id': 5115, 'date': '2015-01-07 18:00:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I agree with Brian that the setup.cfg needs to be changed to put neutron-dhcp-agent-dhsmasq-lease-init as a console script instead of creating a new script.  In that case the bin/neutron-dhcp-agent-dnsmasq-lease-init file is no longer necessary.

I have backported to icehouse and tested in devstack and it does work properly as a console script.'}, {'account_id': 161, 'date': '2015-01-07 18:01:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

With that being said, I still wonder if it wouldn't be better to call _iter_hosts again for getting the hosts to build the leases, rather than pulling it from the hosts file we just wrote out.

I've seen lots of cases where something goes wrong, the code excepts, a message gets lost or whatever and it leads to a hosts file having extra entries in it or not every entry.

I'd think it'd be better to rely on the DB as the source of truth rather than assuming the hosts file got written out properly and potentially leading to a cascade a failures."}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-01-07 21:33:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

@Kevin - since this is a class method doing the reading it can't call self._iter_hosts(), it's using the HOSTS= environment variable to know what host file to read.

@Han - Mike and I have tested that this seems to work for us, just had one more comment on the lease time being used.  If you can cleanup the setup.cfg stuff I think it would be good to go.  Thanks."}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-01-07 21:41:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Fix dnsmasq lease lost upon restart

Generate fake lease during startup of dnsmasq for each entry in
hosts file, with the help of --dhcp-script init function.

Change-Id: I8230dc0ee30efef236b6827dd7116aba88df79de
Closes-Bug: 1345947

commit_message:
Explain how to adopt a backlog spec

Now that we are starting to get backlog specs, make it clear how one can
take it over and implement it.

* Make it clear on the landing page that backlog specs are looking for
  owners. Hopefully this will guide developers looking for a spec to
  work in to the right place.
* Explain how to take over a backlog spec.

Change-Id: Ia3585c515c115e073c00e3222fc6718da79792b9

commit_message:
OVS-agent: Ignore IPv6 addresses for ARP spoofing prevention

The flow rules to match on ARP headers for spoofing prevention
fail to install when an IPv6 address is used. These should be
skipped since the ARP spoofing prevention doesn't apply to IPv6.

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/common/machine_fixtures.py

Co-authored-by: Kevin Benton <blak111@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1449363
Change-Id: I4bb3135e62378c5c96d1ac0b646336ac9a637bde
(cherry picked from commit dbe7ba1868f35af0142f78c70693ed69e6f42ca3)

commit_message:
Add standard QoS spec support to cDOT drivers

This commit adds support for standard cinder QoS specs to
NetApp cDOT drivers, alongside our pre-existing support for
externally provisioned QoS policy groups via qualified
extra specs.

Implements-blueprint: add-qos-spec-support

Change-Id: I4bd123020d00866a346ad02919ac1d82f7236134

commit_message:
post-deploy hook for rhel registration

Adds a potential usage of the post-deploy hooks to register a server
with RHN or a satellite.

Note this requires some additional parameters, which can be specified in
environment_rhel_reg.yaml, and this must be passed into the call to heat
via another -e parameter.  An alternative may be to have a global
extraconfig_env.yaml at the top level, which the scripts always pass, or
to use the global environment (/etc/heat/environment.d/default.yaml) on
the seed.

Co-Authored-By: James Slagle <jslagle@redhat.com>
Change-Id: Ia6fd270122cbc2e51beb672654e5e1ebd3bd2966

commit_message:
Remove requirements_style_check.sh

Per mordred, requirements should be listed in the order they
need to be installed, since pip doesn't "fix" anything listed
in the wrong order.

See also https://review.openstack.org/#/c/92221/

Conflicts:
	requirements.txt

Change-Id: I467a3e597ffca24de01ed3d6bcbc26bd1501353b
(cherry picked from commit 93db699a99793288464fe56de27bcf676fcedd17)

commit_message:
Fix launch-instance dialog when using Postgres

When using Postgres as backend DB for Cinder, searching for bootable=1
does not work:

Caught error: (ProgrammingError) operator does not exist: boolean =
integer

Change-Id: I765eea00b3d0fc81dcf87f83b1f7da1869e8f714
Closes-Bug: #1457153

commit_message:
Improved layout of deployments/_logs.html

Before logs were displayed in a pre tag and to add colors autoescape was
turned off. This leads to potential security vulnerability, because
reports can potentially include malicious js code.

This pactch puts back autoescape, improves the layout,
while preserving the look and feel of the original logs tab,
including color highlights. All the layout logic is moved from python
code to html template and css files.

Change-Id: Ice0101678ff50f00306b69c301f7b4177c584ca1
Closes-Bug: #1460075

commit_message:
Sync strutils from oslo-incubator for mask_password fix

This sync pulls in:
   1131b56 Enable mask_password to handle byte code strings

This is needed because Nova commands are hitting the same
problem Cinder was hitting in bug 1368527 which was fixed
by this strutils update in bug 1366189.

This is not needed in kilo because in kilo Nova has moved
to using the oslo.utils library, which has this fix in it.

NOTE(jecarey):
This is now needed in stable/icehouse because of the backport of:
   f58d95c9 - Sync process and str utils from oslo
which was to address CVE-2014-7231 (bug #1345233)

Note that during icehouse mask_password was moved from
oslo-incubator log.py to strutils.py, however both still exist and
are used.  In order to minimize change, this patch also updates
the original nova/openstack/common/log.py.

Closes-bug: #1366189
Change-Id: I983feea4ac26e34032fa66a4b55f0ce42699ba6a
(cherry picked from commit 0bad3b14abe54926b73acdab8e9b31cae4a87e47)

commit_message:
Escape app names, returned to horizon modal forms

When adding an app to the environment via plus button on the form of
another app an ajax request is made by horizon js code, to get the name
of the app, that was just added to env. Name of the app can contain
malicious code (alternatively the code can be present in the initial
value of the name).

This patch escapes name, returned during that request.

Change-Id: I31f63ed1aa0d46496978110f45c7b43a04519970
Closes-Bug: #1460493

commit_message:
Relax Pillow requirement

Pillow can be used by Django for the ImageField and versions < 2.7.0
shouldn't be used (see CVE-2014-9601).
So allow at least version greater that 2.4.0

Change-Id: I585647eb605fb913e86cce98b4b61116954f1dad

commit_message:
Fix phrase in wait_upgrade_is_done method

- We wait for upgrade is done in tests by
phrase - '*** UPGRADE DONE SUCCESSFULLY' but
it has been changed to
'*** UPGRADING MASTER NODE DONE SUCCESSFULLY'

Change-Id: Iee07ed1cd3530f6578b53b7a102aa0b7ad561a2d
Closes-Bug: #1460578

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: I1b66bd149aba75e565acd0d23e15a1b489ee710d

Christian, I got your point that this maybe be not the best place for this type of content.
In general most of the Linux distros come out with some sort of cloudified images. Server images are optimize to run on real hardware, not as a VMs. So using them to install as a VM is probably not what was intended. There are probably differences in set of pre-installed packages other than that cloud images can be use to build server VMs.
IMHO, having these (complicated and error prone) procedures how to install system inside VM outside of OpenStack environment and cloudyfy them later on has not much value nowadays when we have cloud ready images but this is just my opinion.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-05-06 08:44:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

The intention of the section "Create images manually" is how to build a new image using the server ISO files, not how to use the already existing cloud images. In a lot of productive enterprise environments it is not possible to use existing cloud images and a lot of people want to create there own cloud images (inside or outside from OpenStack).'}, {'account_id': 7923, 'date': '2015-05-09 09:25:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Update Fedora image VM guide example to F21

Rewrite Fedora image example. The latest Fedora 21 comes with dedicated for
cloud usage images. These images provide a base system dedicated for use in
public and private cloud environments. These are cloud-init enabled striped
versions of Fedora. Prior to version 21, to cloudify Fedora images, it was
necessary to perform full manual installation outside of OpenStack, perform
specific configuration and manually cloud-init installation. New Fedora Cloud
images do not require any additional modification and are ready to use. Old
complicated procedure for F20 become irrelevant for F21.

Change-Id: I4c135e2a82f33cbd5fe618e3a34b7a9ab00e11fd
Closes-bug: #1443815

commit_message:
Fixing sending the result of subworkflow

 * This is why retry didn't work for subworkflow
 * Engine commands such as fail or succeed doesn't send the
   result of current workflow to parent workflow if needed.

Closes-Bug: #1449298

Change-Id: Ia0d87160a51f53a686ca0451a2000298cec5a929

commit_message:
API: remove admin require for compute_node_create/update/delete from db layer

This patch removes require_admin_context decorator for compute_node_create
compute_node_update, compute_node_delete.

The 3 methods are not called by any REST api method but only nova code.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part

Change-Id: If15ee5158d2251dafd45f96eb1f0992562f6ba2d

This patch removes require_admin_context decorator from db api, we can safely

1. compute_nodes_get_by_service_id:

should be an admin.

    same with compute_nodes_get_by_service_id.

3. compute_node_get_all_by_host:
    hosts.py->show() method, we have configure admin_rule in policy.json.

Implement blueprint nova-api-policy-final-part
Change-Id: If31c2fd262dd94bb8041f6ae92fc949df14b338a

commit_message:
API: remove admin require from compute_node_get_all_by_* from db layer

This patch removes require_admin_context decorator from db api, we can safely
remove them because of:

1. compute_nodes_get_by_service_id:
    * called by get_by_host_and_nodename which is used by nove(it's admin
context)
    * called by build_and_run_instance if user require a specify node, they
should be an admin.

2. compute_node_get_by_host_and_nodename:
    same with compute_nodes_get_by_service_id.

3. compute_node_get_all_by_host:
    hosts.py->show() method, for v2.1 we have admin_api in policy.json,
for v2, add hard code in rest api for backward-compatible.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part
Change-Id: If31c2fd262dd94bb8041f6ae92fc949df14b338a

commit_message:
API: remove instance_get_all_by_host(_and_node) hard-code admin check from db

This patch removes require_admin_context decorator for instance_get_all_by_host
and instance_get_all_by_host_and_node from db api, will add back-compatible in
v2 REST api layer, for v2.1 we have policy rule to do this checking.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part
Change-Id: Ibec6cc8299d5b2678e4e6c17c6fe2f47a23e9061

commit_message:
Test importing a package by URL

Sets up an httpd SimpleHttpServer, that serves files from a temporary
directory. Package is then put into that directory and imported from it
by url. Directory is removed afterwards.
Includes small speed-ups for tests and improvements for test code
robustness.

Change-Id: I28e70350279daf4ab9b20959d060ca48ffb9162f

commit_message:
Updating cmd/manage.py get_arg_string() argument parser and adding unit test

Looks like get_arg_string() would improperly chop off the first two characters
of an argument that was passed in with one dash.  For example,
passing '-option foo' would return 'tion foo' instead of 'option foo'.

Change-Id: Ib9aee601711b22c5243aca35f5c6196f494d23a9
Closes-Bug: #1459453

commit_message:
Neutron: Remove hiera lookup to controller_host

With current effort of creating isolated networks, the controller_host
hiera variable does not exist anymore. Hence we remove it else the
lookup will fail.

The hiera binding neutron::agents::ml2::ovs::local_ip has been written
in another review[1]

[1] I1dc11987b4ea3c37775b14fbdddb75588499e9bb

Change-Id: I12777c512d379210e5cddb5e683be4d79808fa2c

commit_message:
Replaced setting run_pause with standard interval

The deprecated directive `run_pause` should be replaced with the more
standard one `interval`. The `run_pause` should be still supported for
backward compatibility. This patch updates object replicator to use
`interval` and support `run_pause`. It also updates its sample config
and documentation.

Co-Authored-By: Joanna H. Huang <joanna.huitzu.huang@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Kamil Rykowski <kamil.rykowski@intel.com>

Change-Id: Ie2a3414a96a94efb9273ff53a80b9d90c74fff09
Closes-Bug: #1364735

commit_message:
Fix TemplateDoesNotExist at manage/unmanage volumes

manage/unmanage template includes wrong templates:

project/volumes/volumes/_unmanage_volume.html
project/volumes/volumes/_manage_volume.html

it should be admin/volumes/... instead of project/volumes/...

Change-Id: Ic1b16077630b39b8a72e773c562de2c65a5a11c3
Closes-Bug: #1459625
(cherry picked from commit c5b287ebf24df478c9aeea47840da197c6e5a2d6)

subject: Support CIS service in glanceclient
messages:
[{'account_id': 13161, 'date': '2015-04-15 08:22:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 13161, 'date': '2015-04-15 08:24:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 13161, 'date': '2015-04-15 08:26:10.000000000', 'content': 'Topic set to bp/catalog-index-service-client'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-15 08:30:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-glance-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/18/173718/2/check/gate-glance-specs-docs/ce035a1//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 38s
- gate-glance-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/18/173718/2/check/gate-glance-specs-python27/a63551b/ : SUCCESS in 2m 08s'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:13:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I believe this is not consistent with Glance's mission statement.

Glance should not expose general purpose  -- potentially unrelated to images, artifacts or even OpenStack -- Elastic Search capabilities to users."}, {'account_id': 13161, 'date': '2015-04-16 14:52:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Catalog Index Service has become a part of Glance in the Kilo release and even it's marked as an experimental feature
we should somehow provide an easy way to work with it. Right now the only way to play with it is to use tools such as
curl to send requests to the CIS search API which is not convenient for end-users. I realize that providing such functionality
to glanceclient still requires from end-user some basic knowledge of building queries for Elasticsearch
(as CIS is strictly connected with it right now), but it will be still simpler to use it instead of some generic tools
for transferring HTTP requests.

That's more about exposing Glance CIS into glanceclient than Elasticsearch capabilities."}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-04-20 15:42:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

This should be rebased on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/163382/'}, {'account_id': 13161, 'date': '2015-04-21 06:43:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-21 06:47:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-glance-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/18/173718/3/check/gate-glance-specs-docs/ef6ac5d//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 56s
- gate-glance-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/18/173718/3/check/gate-glance-specs-python27/6576fae/ : SUCCESS in 2m 04s'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-04-21 15:07:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I'm very -1 on this in its current state. This really need to be discussed at the Summit in a few weeks. I don't think I'll be comfortable with a spec, however, that allows users to upload arbitrary documents to Elasticsearch via Glance. I would rather see Glance be the only "way" to upload documents relating to glance. If users want to upload arbitrary documents to Elasticsearch they certainly should contact their administrator/operator to expose Elasticsearch.'}, {'account_id': 13161, 'date': '2015-04-22 09:36:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Ian: Thanks for feedback. I totally agree that such thing should be somehow discussed at the Summit. It can be not clear for everyone if this should be a part of the glanceclient or how should it looks like. Personally I don't think that discussion about IF is a valid topic, because we've already implemented backend for CIS at the Glance side and you cannot say A without saying B. Still the discussion about how glanceclient should operate on CIS needs to be defined in the near future.

Would like to also address your concern that proposed shape of spec allows user to upload arbitrary documents to Elasticsearch (ES is the engine used under the hood, we should rather talk about uploading documents to CIS service) which are not related to Glance in any way (images & metadefs in current implementation). During the Kilo release, we - by we I mean the team responsible for implementing the CIS - have discussed such scenario, that exposing Elasticsearch capabilities to the user consuming the CIS API can bring some serious security impact. Simply
imagine scenario where CIS is enabled at the infrastructure which already uses some ES cluster for storing data (e.g. logs for applications) and operator would like to re-use existing cluster for the CIS purpose instead of maintaining a separate cluster. User could easily use the CIS API to delete all existing log documents (even by accident, providing wrong index in the query deleting all documents). It has been handled by using the plugin system for available CIS resources which prevents operating (reading and writing) on documents which don't have corresponding plugin registered. Right now any access to resources stored outside of index name `glance` and document type `image` and `metadef` is forbidden by CIS. User is only allowed to play with documents which are registered within CIS.

Unfortunately I won't be able to attend the Vancouver Summit this time (wish to!). That's bad as I would really like to discuss this topic outside the gerrit
review and talk about it in the non-virtual world."}, {'account_id': 13161, 'date': '2015-04-23 08:04:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2015-04-24 00:31:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Hi Kamil,

I do agree with Stuart and Ian here. Now if we allow uploading arbitrary documents in the current experimental CIS API implementation, that security hole needs to plugged rather than expanded to client ability as well. Thankfully the API is experimental and noted to be possibly changed in backwards incompatible way.

The current Glance mission statement nor the spec describing CIS doesn't grant this service being used multipurpose elasticsearch interface, but rather specific use case to improve the searchability of the assets withing specified data sets (at least widely understood to be provided by glance services).

I do not believe that anyone in our core team would have let detail like this to slip intentionally, but more being an overlook while the rush on the reviews to make this into Kilo at all.

Please note that as long as CIS is developed under Glance Project statement like "which are not related to Glance in any way", how ever refined, obsolete. (perhaps not to Image API nor Artifact API, but Glance, definitely) 

As you brought it up, I'd like to also ask why these concerns, "that exposing Elasticsearch capabilities to the user consuming the CIS API can bring some serious security impact.", were not documented in the spec under Security Impact if they have been discussed already during the cycle? One reason for those fields being there is to provide the information also to reviewers so that extra attention can be paid to such concerns during the implementation/review.

I do agree that this topic needs to be discussed @ the Summit. I'm sorry to hear that you cannot be there in person to provide your insight. I hope we can find satisfactory solution or at least direction for everyone during future discussions.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2015-04-30 16:13:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Kamil

The Glance Registry services requests which originate from the  Glance API (or some operator specific commands whose code lives in the 'glance' repo). We don't have commands in python-glanceclient which go directly to the Registry port. 

In the case of CIS is the model similar, ie the Glance API, or a script which lives in the 'glance' repo generates the requests which the CIS port services?

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 13161, 'date': '2015-06-01 06:32:14.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Moving to Searchlight project - https://launchpad.net/searchlight'}]

commit_message:
Support CIS service in glanceclient

This is intended to add functionality to python-glanceclient to support
Catalog Index Service by exposing commands for searching and managing
data stored within it.

bp catalog-index-service-client

Change-Id: I77ae35af1c44e12c0a8eda33d75e29d14c66cb2e

WIP: Index service utils commands

This patch provides some utility methods and commands for users which
want to play with the Catalog Index Service.

commit_message:
Catalog Index Service - Client

Implements: blueprint TBD

Provide CLI support for search service by adding commands to operate on
Glance Search API. Following commands has been introduced:

* index-search - used to search for resources across different indices
and types.
* index-manage - used to manage resources stored in search engine.
Provides a way to create, update and delete documents.

Change-Id: Ieface6b23d77eaf36fd5fae962c9959d7e2b1a30

commit_message:
Fix policy check for API 'security service update'

Manila API for update of security service reads policy for "show" operation
but should do it for "update" operation.

Change-Id: I675f834fcb75f3b7864094601e47c15f60a0864b
Closes-Bug: #1459631

From time to time we have itermitent errors regarding the
fake_notifier.NOTIFICATIONS count.

This patch does two things to try to find out which notifications are
being fired unexpectedly:
- Make sure that fake_notifier is reset in cleanup regardless of
  exception raised by shutil.rmtree

'}]
commit_message:
Display NOTIFICATIONS on assert failure

From time to time we have itermitent errors regarding the
fake_notifier.NOTIFICATIONS count.

This patch does two things to try to find out which notifications are
being fired unexpectedly:
- Make sure that fake_notifier is reset in cleanup regardless of
  exception raised by shutil.rmtree
- Display fake_notifier.NOTIFICATIONS whenever count assertion fails.

Related-Bug: #1412513
Change-Id: I07370636d8b30098dcb2a70ef1985c2f5aee81be

commit_message:
Remove unused attr status from models

Models "security_services" and "network_allocations" have attr "status" that is
not used indeed. So, remove it from models and add appropriate migrations.

Closes-Bug: #1459660
Change-Id: Idb3a69916e8052b16c9daebb9bb67b09d1714c46

commit_message:
Report status when engine start

After heat engine starts, it won't report its status, so
updated_at is None by then. If heat engine die before its first
status report, its record will not remove from service-list.

Change-Id: I55801ceb12ec8e4a3746799d3d43c6e9c01c6cd8
Closes-Bug: #1459997

commit_message:
Show the right request body in v2 port update api.

Divide the file port_create_or_update_req.json/xml into 2 different
sample files, named port_create_req.json/xml and port_update_req.json/xml.
And show the right example like others api showed.

Change-Id: I4c5529a81c6b1a0b134eca28818505a243332faa
Closes-bug:#1460500

commit_message:
Ignore cover directory

When the coverage report is generated, it's put into the cover
directory. This should be ignored by git so it's not accidentally
checked in.

Change-Id: I2569b73ab5da1f7b3bb895507b5bbb02b83d6ccb

commit_message:
Passing posargs to flake8

By passing posargs to flake8, we can now test pep8 of a single file by passing
file name, eg:

    tox -e pep8 magnum/common/service.py

Closes-Bug: #1460495
Change-Id: I8e143b25719c6b375dbd9fc550809f417509e65c
