Hi, Mark. Those days, I thought again and again about the implementation with your comments. Since we use lwrp. Seems it is much better if we create a "create_ovs_bridge" resource(require move, bridge_name, iface_name attribtues). This resource will create the bridge, and move the ip to the bridge depend by the ip movement flag. Therefore, all the existing ovs bridge creation "execute" resource can be replaced by this resource. And this will let the code more flexible. However, this change means this BP should be changed again. Because we no need to add recipes again. Just one resource.'}, {'account_id': 11159, 'date': '2015-05-19 09:22:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

For the last comment, it might be inconvenient if ip-movement need to run before any network recipe. In such case, I have to create a recipe to use this resource to do ip-move.
I would suggest to create 2 recipes for ip movement. one is for external network interfaces, the other is for data network interfaces. These 2 recipes will use the resource mentioned in last comment and the node attribute to perform appropriate action.
The recipes will be included at where they are needed(even not in network recipes). So that we don't need to consider l3/vpn/dvr or other things in the new recipes. 
This will keep the code simple and flexible."}, {'account_id': 13667, 'date': '2015-05-19 09:41:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 13667, 'date': '2015-05-19 09:47:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 13667, 'date': '2015-05-19 09:51:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Hong Hui's comments make sense. In case that ip move should be done before recipes like openvswitch or l3_agent, we will need a recipe for ip move."}, {'account_id': 8172, 'date': '2015-05-20 01:30:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Actually, I don't think we need to add more recipe to handle ip movement. If you want to move ip first. Just use this resource in your own recipe to create bridge. This resource will avoid to move ip twice."}, {'account_id': 8172, 'date': '2015-05-20 01:50:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

To Hong Hui's comment. I think it is still not convenient if we want to support multiple bridges for data network and external network in the future. Because it can not avoid checking again and again to make sure we move the correct interface's ip address. Therefore, the code will become difficult to extend and maintenance.

In a word.I think package the ip movement code in a resource, let programmer decide which interface ip should be moved can let the openstack-network-cookbook easier to maintenance and extend. However, if you want a ip movement recipe to satisfy your requirement. I think we can create a single ip movement recipe to handle this(in this bp), this recipe will invoke the new resource. You can just include this new recipe in your own recipe."}, {'account_id': 8172, 'date': '2015-05-20 01:57:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(3 comments)

Thanks for your review.'}, {'account_id': 11159, 'date': '2015-05-20 03:12:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

To hu wei's last comment, I partially understand your concern... Having a single ip-movement recipe will unavoidably make the logic hard to maintain. But I still don't agree your suggest in last comment. Having duplicated code is not a good way. 
May be we can split the check logic and ip-move action away. We can create a node's attribute, something like node[openstack][network][nics_need_ip_move]. Any recipe that wants to move any nic, just need to update this attribute. This will make the check logic simply maintained in recipes that need ip movement. This is your original thought "let programmer decide which interface ip should be moved".
On the other side, we still have a ip-move recipe. :( This recipe will do only one thing --- moving the ip of the nics in node[openstack][network][nics_need_ip_move]. So the usercase I mentioned will be satisfied.'}, {'account_id': 8172, 'date': '2015-05-20 08:09:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-20 08:09:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

building new network resources, a like a bridge seems like a good idea. And then like the package resource, have a specific provider like is done for apt, apt_package.   So, it would be a few resources, a base one, bridge and then another one ovs_bridge.  bridge could have actions like create, delete, and ovs_bridge could have additional actions for move_ip.

Once these resources are available, we can supply a reference recipe that  makes basic use of them for some of the most common types of scenarios.  But since they are resources, now anyone can use them to handle many more  specific environments.'}, {'account_id': 8172, 'date': '2015-05-21 02:05:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Yeah. That's what I want to do. We can replace all the ovs creation execute resource to the new one. And in the future, maybe can add linux bridge support or some others. :)"}, {'account_id': 13667, 'date': '2015-05-21 07:14:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Disable cloud-watch-lite by default

This has been deprecated for years and is incompatible with deploying
multiple heat-engine processes. Let's at least not turn it on by default.

Change-Id: Iabddbd65be9000a30a5714b26658ea6acea0e103

commit_message:
Add test case to 'cidr2netmask'

'cidr2netmask' of function doesn't have enough test case
and test code isn't smart.
This patch adds test case and refactors test code.

Change-Id: Iab20ef06fe78316a78198ab75c0afe738a577dd6
Closes-bug: #1457989

Phew, after reading thru the spec I wonder how easy it will be for folks to understand the schema language. Some validation code in python as it's done today might look easier to some people."}, {'account_id': 12259, 'date': '2015-05-08 08:09:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-05-08 23:45:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Would you guys consider not using the name "property_groups"? We have that in the template syntax, it's going to make things confusing to have two different things with the same name. How about "validation_groups"?

Also, I wanted to mention that there are some types of relationships between properties that I think cannot be expressed with the proposed extension. For example, if you want to say something like "If propertyA is set, then propertyB and propertyC are required, else they must be empty".

I think complex validation rules are hard to express declaratively. I'm a big fan of expressing validation with Python code. Have you seen how project wtforms implements validators for web forms? I think that concept would work really well here, you have a set of pre-defined validators, and more can be defined for special cases.'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2015-05-10 23:41:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

commit_message:
Property Group

Adds property_groups to the properties_schema for resource
plug-in, which helps to declare the validation logic
across dependent properties.

blueprint heat-property-group

Co-Authored-by: Peter Razumovsky<prazumovsky@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: Ia336772657e6a8d38a157a194d5069903c83e37f

commit_message:
Notification with volume and snapshot metadata

Now notify message to ceilometer do not contain volume
metadata/glance_metadata and snapshot metadata, which are
useful to bill and enrich resource information in ceilometer.

This feature will add the metadata/glance_metadata of volume
and metadata of snapshot to notification usage info.

Change-Id: I04097be9f2da1d6bc45a2d5770bcd543a3f41887
Implements: blueprint notification-with-volume-and-snapshot-metadata

commit_message:
Instructions to add a required dependency package

Adds the qemu package to allow creation or importing of QCOW or VMDK
(non-raw) images. Amended to correct style and verbiage errors.

Change-Id: I2919fee543e714a85042d37400c6a6d7faae62e0
Closes-bug: #1406784

commit_message:
Fix translation setup

The infra scripts really expect $REPODIR/locale to work, fix
setup.cfg and rename the locale file so that infra scripts work.

This fixes change Id9f5b08835a4780a8448c989a878c03b70a97803 which
already said:"The proper place is for all python projects
$PROJECT/locale/$PROJECT.pot - see setup.cfg." - but then during review
we missed that instead of PROJECT=python-magnumclient, it used
magnumclient - and the infra scripts do not cope with that since
PROJECT really has to be the name of the repository.

Change-Id: Idc5efe52a1ff1b0cb8599e1258e411522547f0e4

[{'created': '2014-10-30 19:11:53.000000000', 'message': 'Move validation logic out of drivers and managers

Prior to having jsonschema validate incoming requests for Keystone,
there were several different ways to validate input from the user. The
keystone/clean.py module was one of the ways this was done.

From a Keystone V3 perspective, we handle all validation with jsonschema
at the controller layer. With keystone/clean.py, these calls are
scattered throughout the Keystone stack, some in the backends, and some
in the managers, for the Keystone v2.0 API. This commit is an attempt to
standardize a place for keystone/clean.py calls in general, if and only
if we need them, since they are only for v2.0 calls.

Change-Id: I336f641edc82e92cd962f333b841a623635f4400
Related-Bug: #1387607
'}]
commit_message:
Move validation logic out of drivers and managers

Prior to having jsonschema validate incoming requests for Keystone,
there were several different ways to validate input from the user. The
keystone/clean.py module was one of the ways this was done.

From a Keystone V3 perspective, we handle all validation with jsonschema
at the controller layer. With keystone/clean.py, these calls are
scattered throughout the Keystone stack, some in the backends, and some
in the managers, for the Keystone v2.0 API. This commit is an attempt to
standardize a place for keystone/clean.py calls in general, if and only
if we need them, since they are only for v2.0 calls.

Change-Id: I336f641edc82e92cd962f333b841a623635f4400
Related-Bug: #1387607

commit_message:
Fix continuation line under/over indented problems

When you are writing a multiple method invocation (or other similar
syntax)

```
obj.method(argument1,
           argument2,
           ...)
```

If you put argument1 in the first line, the following lines should have
the same hanging distance to argument1.

If you put argument1 in the second line, the hanging distance should
always be four.

```
obj.method(
    argument1,
    argument2,
    ...
)
```

Otherwise PEP8 would complain for continuation line under/over indented
problems. See below for more details

https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#indentation

This patch fixes all the continuation line indentation problems and
enables related checks in tox.ini.

Closes-bug: #1459514
Change-Id: I80995c2ae71b817ad78a87ab7c567f0d36112710

The change itself looks good, I have just a documentation suggestion.

But I don't thing this will really fix anything for nova. If 'multipath -r' stuck, next time nova run it, it have a good chance to be stuck again and again. How can we be sure that the compute node is still usable ? 

More generally having a command that stucks is not a good news. Unblock the application is good things, but keep the system into a unknown state.

commit_message:
Add timeout parameter to execute

Add an optional timeout parameter to execute() function of
oslo_concurrency.processutils. Timeout is 0 means infinity,
which is the default.

Add new tests.

This changeset does not change the default behaviour.

Closes-Bug: #1448227

Change-Id: I0dfdf5b28ad26b2255c76a0b5c4c1ced1f813216

commit_message:
Enable random hash seeds

Neutron tests have been updated in order to support random hash seed. It
allows to remove PYTHONHASHSEED=0 in tox.ini and remove hashtest tox
environment.

Closes-Bug: #1348818
Change-Id: I1063304dda887eb82c0de8516d5a483fa8943fc1

commit_message:
Update functional tox env requirements

The functional tox env requirements were in tox.ini, so they weren't
being updated automatically and were out of date.

The functional tox env requirements are moved to
test-requirements-functional.txt so that they'll be updated
automatically and the requirements are updated to the
requirements as of 8cb51513 .

Change-Id: I90ff294914487d6beee5564c2c541f7f77bb3361

    In case you have SELinux enabled and rally fails to create the database,

commit_message:
[WIP] Change the structure of Ironic's developer documentation (Don't Merge)

We don't have OpenStack Documentation for kilo written by docs team.
So for Admins, we should keep the Install Guide etc for stable/kilo.

On the other hand, we should also keep the Developer Install Guide for master.

We should create a branch of guide for stable/kilo other than
what we maintain for master.

Change-Id: Iaaf2b4d04adb113be1177623f94a524838bb89ec

commit_message:
Removed duplicate keys in dicts in test

Test test_create_security_group_rule_invalid_ethertype_for_prefix
contained dict with duplicate keys, remote ip prefixes.

Test was successful because incorrect items for tests were overwitten:

'192.168.1.1/24': 'ipv4'  by '192.168.1.1/24': 'IPv6'
'2001:db8:1234::/48': 'ipv6' by '2001:db8:1234::/48': 'IPv4'

This patch removes incorrect and useless items for tests.
Also added additional item with invalid ethertype.

Change-Id: I29cd2b843a7905986de13a1ecfba0cb5797ccaf8

commit_message:
Check only for added/deleted metadata entries

Utilize the same methodology as test_volume_metadata and only check
for presence or absence of metadata entries explicitily touched on
the snapshot.

Update_snapshot_metadata requires testing for exact match (it
replaces, not appends).

Change-Id: I2be45ff13997269b39de85d16ccaea3504e972cc
Closes-Bug: 1379460

commit_message:
Verify exact match for volume metadata update.

Test_update_volume_metadata completely replaces a volume's existing
metadata with a new set, discarding any existing values.  Change the
assertion check to an exact match, not merely contains(), to ensure
that no stale metadata is present after update_all.

Change-Id: I1d363cfa65cb7c76fae9cfabaa499dcdf7c8b0ca
Closes-Bug: 1459351

commit_message:
Do not consider subnets of shared public nets

Test test_external_network_visibility in
tempest.api.network.test_network fails when running
tempest against a deployment with public networks which
are shared among non-admin tenants.

This patch skips the public networks whose shared
property is set to true, as their subnets will be visible to
non-admin tenants.

Change-Id: Ieafb8e4094e603e259d68c4f485194a602dfc0cf
Closes-Bug: #1425962

commit_message:
Set Rabbit recovery method for network partitions

Adds configurable option rabbit_cluster_partition_handling with default
value of pause_minority. Allows option to be explicitly set to ignore
through Ansible to reset to prior (and RabbitMQ default) behavior.

Closes-Bug: #1454860
(cherry picked from commit af1b69cb1e7f456e19b391802097fe8d59a4ff1c)

Change-Id: Ife58b94142bc0a846da5c0db854c5852f318730a

commit_message:
Volume replication enablement for IBM storwize/SVC

Add replication support to IBM storwize/SVC driver.
Supports replication modes:
1. Metro Mirror
2. Global Mirror

WIP: Unit test, reenable_replcation will be added

Change-Id: I77dc2e7221544c5d355671710a48a7ca61afbeff

commit_message:
Add support for volume v2 API

Added following commands for volume V2 API:
volume show
volume delete
volume type show
volume type delete
snapshot show
snapshot delete
backup show
backup delete

Implements: blueprint volume-v2
Change-Id: I68bd303c194f304ad15f899d335b72a8bf3ebe10

commit_message:
Sync oslo-incubator cc19617

Sync oslo-inclubator files to commit
cc19617bf7dc633a9395e8db33835840d70298e2 .

Changes since last commit:

 $ git log --oneline --no-merges f2cfbba..cc19617 -- \
 openstack/common/eventlet_backdoor.py
 openstack/common/fileutils.py
 openstack/common/loopingcall.py
 openstack/common/service.py
 openstack/common/threadgroup.py

16eb642 Clean up logging to conform to guidelines
97ba6db Port service to Python 3
702bc56 service child process normal SIGTERM exit
64b5819 Revert "Revert "Revert "Optimization of waiting subprocesses in ProcessLauncher"""
f5646ed Revert "Revert "Optimization of waiting subprocesses in ProcessLauncher""
d24b658 Revert "Optimization of waiting subprocesses in ProcessLauncher"
593005b ProcessLauncher: reload config file in parent process on SIGHUP
f29e865 Store ProcessLauncher signal handlers on class level

Change-Id: Ie31ef57e847f11b9e322aa8c05f95b62b0dae61e

commit_message:
VMware: insecure option should be exposed

Commit Ida730db66b154a4d445f7a91bccb9ca5b5a26f5e introduced
certificate verification but did not expose the option to turn
on/off verification using the insecure boolean of oslo.vmware.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I834c9fb407c8790dab14db0308f7e7f1d551669e
Closes-Bug: #1451633

commit_message:
Add "enabled" to create service provider example

By default, the SP is disabled. It should be enabled in order to
retrieve a SAML assertion targeted to it.

commit_message:
Display ID column in the Security Group table

This patch set is to add ID column in the security group table.
This is useful when there are multiple security group that has the
same name.

commit_message:
Refactor: Join multiple criteria together

Filtering criterion in the method of "Query.filter_by()" or
"Query.filter()" introduced by SQLAlchemy supports to join
multiple criteria together instead of join each criteria
separately.

The motivation to make this change includes,
1. The docstring in the SQLAlchemy tell us the usage,
" Multiple criteria are joined together by AND::

   session.query(MyClass).\\
      filter(MyClass.name == 'some name', MyClass.id > 5)"

or
" Multiple criteria are joined together by AND::

   session.query(MyClass).\\
      filter_by(name = 'some name', id = 5)
"

Since SQLAlchemy provides this interface, this should has
its benefit from introducing this method, the direct impact
is we needn't build the query statement repetitively.

2. The change make the code looks more concise.

Closes-Bug: #1449850
Change-Id: Iddf6b23a538c0bd05e69c9a170240058e1ed1b98

commit_message:
add domain scope arguments to v3 role add in doc

There are optional domain scope arguments --user-domain,
--group-domain and --project-domain to filter user, group
and project for command 'os role add', however, the doc
is missing them.

Closes-Bug: #1460296
Change-Id: Ie7c7707d183da042c51e98b6cd4003c89efc4032

commit_message:
Fix wrong request type in os-quota-sets

The request type for Update quotas for user in os-quota-sets
should be 'PUT',not 'POST'

Change-Id: I59c923b08818ff4468d238db9d854f052168e2ab
Closes-bug:#1459125

[{'created': '2015-05-28 17:50:10.000000000', 'message': 'Add launchpad tag used by "Report a bug"

"Report a bug" automatically populates bugs on launchpad with
information about the manual. This additional config setting
will allow "Report a bug" to automatically tag the bug with the
respective manual.

Change-Id: Ia46756f9e9e9f0ee117a821403ef1dbef0434b6e
'}]
commit_message:
Add launchpad tag used by "Report a bug"

"Report a bug" automatically populates bugs on launchpad with
information about the manual. This additional config setting
will allow "Report a bug" to automatically tag the bug with the
respective manual.

Change-Id: Ia46756f9e9e9f0ee117a821403ef1dbef0434b6e

commit_message:
Improve test_set_members_deleting_less_than_5

In test_set_members_deleting_less_than_5[1], 3 ips are deleted from
ipset but test_set_members_deleting_less_than_5 checked that the
first one was deleted because the call ordering was non-trivial.

The test was successful because
assert_has_calls(expected_calls, any_order=False) allows extra calls
before and after expected_calls.

A parent change[2] forces the call ordering, this allows to check that
the 3 ips are deleted.

[1] neutron.tests.unit.agent.linux.test_ipset_manager
[2] I8408365825ec1e97a83c2181f38ec1f9468df91e

Related-Bug: #1348818

[{'created': '2015-05-30 11:42:29.000000000', 'message': 'Remove use of contextlib.nested (db-tests)

Removed use of contextlib.nested call from codebase, as it has been
deprecated since Python 2.7.

There are also known issues with contextlib.nested that were addressed
by the native support for multiple "with" variables. For instance, if
the first object is created but the second one throws an exception,
the first object's __exit__ is never called. For more information see
https://docs.python.org/2/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.nested
contextlib.nested is also not compatible with Python 3.

Multi-patch set for easier chunks. This one addresses the tests from
neutron/tests/unit/db directory.

Line continuation markers (e.g. '\') had to be used or syntax
errors were thrown. While using parentheses is the preferred way
for multiple line statements, but in case of long with statements
backslashes are acceptable.

Partial-Bug: 1428424
Change-Id: I8eee732427188cc0c5e8dde25d1d6e10cf21cc12
'}]
commit_message:
Remove use of contextlib.nested (db-tests)

Removed use of contextlib.nested call from codebase, as it has been
deprecated since Python 2.7.

There are also known issues with contextlib.nested that were addressed
by the native support for multiple "with" variables. For instance, if
the first object is created but the second one throws an exception,
the first object's __exit__ is never called. For more information see
https://docs.python.org/2/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.nested
contextlib.nested is also not compatible with Python 3.

Multi-patch set for easier chunks. This one addresses the tests from
neutron/tests/unit/db directory.

Line continuation markers (e.g. '\') had to be used or syntax
errors were thrown. While using parentheses is the preferred way
for multiple line statements, but in case of long with statements
backslashes are acceptable.

Partial-Bug: 1428424
Change-Id: I8eee732427188cc0c5e8dde25d1d6e10cf21cc12

commit_message:
Fix branch for keystone bandit job

While the bandit job should only run on master for now, once the
next release is done it should work on the new stable branch, so
the job should only be skipped for the current stable branches.

Change-Id: I3b75d7aa520038a7ebe8f118b6a395cf50ccfeec

task report: generate a JUnit report

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: I176520571c15bac461dfe7eed4b6cf2eca161c3f

commit_message:
VMware: add support for ToolsUnavailableException

Provide a stop gap for this exception until the next oslo.vmware
version lands.

Change-Id: I0c2ab3107e5f4752ab77cb5ab24568fc6e27be89

commit_message:
Remove discover dependency

discover is not needed to run tests: oslotest is based on
testtools.run which uses unittest to discover tests. On Python 2.6,
unittest2 backport is used to get the discover feature.

Change-Id: Ice0f82251b77ab826a436cf7e5aed2573412e933

commit_message:
Defer creation of router JSON in get_routers RPC

The get_routers method in the l3 RPC code has a log.debug
statement that formats all of the router data as indented
JSON. This method can be expensive if there are hundreds
of routers being synced and it happens even if debugging
is disabled since the function call result is the parameter
to the debug statement.

This patch adds and leverages a small helper class that takes a
callable and its args and defers calling it until the __str__ method
is called on it when it's actually trying to be rendered to a string.

Change-Id: I2bfceb286ce30f2a3595381b62bdc6dd71ed8483
Partial-Bug: #1445412
(cherry picked from commit 649599457e29b58ad0aec9ace990e0a2b59b05d0)

Fix formatting of core-reviewers doc

Fix some RST formatting issues with the core-reviewers policy document.

When reading the RST rendered version of that document at
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/neutron/policies/core-reviewers.html

commit_message:
Get completely rid of contextlib.nested

`contextlib.nested` is deprecated since Python 2.7 and incompatible with
Python 3. This patch removes all its occurences by using the helper
script at [1].

This is a necessary step to allow us running all unit tests with
Python 3 (not just a small subset as it is done now).

[1]: https://github.com/adrienverge/context_unnester

Change-Id: I8d1de09ff38ed0af9fb56f423a2c43476408e0fb
Blueprint: neutron-python3
Closes-Bug: #1428424

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: Id48540c741b74eb3b4b9ecf84fb7f034631d04b5

commit_message:
Rename federated.py to federation.py

Rename the plugins, as we usually use ``federation` instead of
``federated``. Also the stub class was renamed from
``FederatedBaseAuth`` to ``FederationBaseAuth``.

Change-Id: I696c16b9683b42c358c3b17b02e425e0b69014ea

commit_message:
Workaround db2 dialect bug in migrate 73

When running migration 73, the DB2 dialect tries to create an
index on just the `inherited` column unlike the mysql dialect
which just updates the metadata.

A workaround is provided until the DB2 dialect bug can be fixed.

The bug reported against the DB2 dialect is
https://code.google.com/p/ibm-db/issues/detail?id=173

Related-Bug: 1453419
Change-Id: Ia9a28c31ad9a6970c6ad8d243393ab4b4fe07880

commit_message:
Fix indentation errors in tests

They are some missing/extra indentations in tests source code. This
results in variables used out their scope (which remains unnoticed as
long as `with` contexts do not fail), and prevent refactoring scripts
(such as the one for getting rid of `contextlib.nested` [1]) from
performing well.

This simple patch fixes these indentation errors.

[1]: See change I8d1de09ff38ed0af9fb56f423a2c43476408e0fb

Change-Id: Icef34c7755e0d96c4c5ee85982de86d0ccc196c7
Related-Blueprint: neutron-python3

commit_message:
Removes unused database setup code

We currently use in-memory SQLite for testing. Previously we created
a file on disk and reused a pristine version of it to save setup time.
We can delete this code since we no longer do this.

Change-Id: I2eabf0c3624d47efbe8c4136cfa8a922e9ed5410

commit_message:
`api_curl_examples.rst` is out of date

Part of CURL response is not accurate anymore
- There will be no service catalog returned if we get
  a token from a existing token.
- Miss `audit_ids` in the response.

Closes-Bug: #1459532
Change-Id: I81db8db37f4ffdad01f976a16c14f45f411db76d

commit_message:
Remove randomness from test_client_socket_timeout

This maintains the same test coverage but does so in a single test,
eliminating the possibility of a transient.

This fixes a nit noted in:

  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130824/18/keystone/tests/unit/test_wsgi.py

Change-Id: Ief73ca8e7def94c3e2f85650c060f8d72bae565f

commit_message:
Fix auth required message translation

Passing a string that is formatted into a translation function doesn't
work. We need to pass the full translatable string.

Change-Id: I94b13f18c19b3b872fab380f8822a88db1b876e9

commit_message:
Create instance_extra entry if it doesn't update

When updating an instance, if there is no instance_extra, for older
instances, we make sure we create one if there is not one already.

This keeps flavor data migrations (ie system_metadata ->
instance_extra) from failing when the system_metadata entries are soft
deleted but an instance_extra entry is not created because it was
"updated" assuming an instance_extra entry already existed, leaving
the instance with no flavor data.

Closes-Bug: #1459758
Change-Id: I715217d98729c6c5ac45d64d8bacaaca745ff3d7

[{'account_id': 7776, 'date': '2015-05-28 20:05:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-05-28 20:17:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Not a typo, and this patch also needs a triaged bug associated with it. In addition to the usual 127.0.0.1 entry pointing to localhost (necessary), Ubuntu often adds another entry with 127.0.1.1 pointing to the actual hostname. The latter entry tends to cause problems with name resolution.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-28 20:19:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checklinks http://logs.openstack.org/54/186554/1/check/gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checklinks/f882b9c/ : SUCCESS in 2m 38s (non-voting)

Ah, ok. In that case I think an elaboration in the wording of the warning would be a good idea. 127.0.0.1 is such a well known IP that I actually read this section of the install guide multiple times before without even noticing the 1 in the third octet. When I finally noticed the 1 my immediate thought was that it was a typo. It did not even occur to me that Ubuntu would add an extraneous unusual loopback IP.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-05-28 20:36:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Can you file a bug and suggest some wording?'}, {'account_id': 7776, 'date': '2015-05-28 20:51:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I filed https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-manuals/+bug/1459825 with a suggested addition to the warning. This would have saved me some head scratching on why OpenStack was (I thought) asking me to remove the localhost entry. I'm still curious as to why it causes problems and why Ubuntu and others would add it automatically if it causes problems. I wonder if there's a deeper bug in the actual code."}, {'account_id': 7776, 'date': '2015-05-28 21:27:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7776, 'date': '2015-05-28 21:31:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-28 21:43:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

http://www.debian.org/doc/manuals/debian-reference/ch05.en.html#_the_hostname_resolution explains why this entry is done this way. It's not a bug, it's a workaround for a potential class of other bugs. The referenced one is with GNOME, but there can certainly be others. Most *n?x systems just add extra hostnames to the localhost entry as alternates, but Debian-derived distros use other loopback addresses when there isn't a known, static IP at installation time. Otherwise, they use that IP to associate the specified hostname of the box with, leaving only "localhost" associated with 127.0.0.1.

That said, the entire 127/8 block is valid when referring to the loopback interface on a *n?x machine. Every last one of those 16,777,214 IPs will resolve to "lo", which is why Debian's workaround works perfectly fine. I don't think it needs to be changed or removed from documentation for being "confusing", unless it's causing a real, tangible issue during operation or configuration of your environment.'}, {'account_id': 7776, 'date': '2015-05-29 01:33:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Evan, That page is an interesting read although it didn't enlighten me on exactly what the bug is that's Debian is working around with this extra loopback IP. It makes me even more curious about whether removing this IP is a good idea without understanding what bug its presence is supposed to fix.
However, I'm not suggesting that the warning should be removed. I'm saying that even after reading it multiple times I was positive that that the manual was instructing me to remove the 127.0.0.1 localhost entry. I even posted a question to ask.o.o (https://ask.openstack.org/en/question/66957/why-does-the-install-guide-say-to-remove-127001-from-etchosts/) asking why the install guide instructed to remove 127.0.0.1. Anne Gentle replied to me without either noticing or pointing out that I had misread the manual. What I've proposed in patch set 3 is simply a more verbose warning that makes it perfectly clear that the guide is saying to remove 127.0.1.1, NOT 127.0.0.1. I agree with you that 127.0.1.1 is a valid loopback, but this usage is so obscure that I would think that other people would make the same mistake I did and just read it as 127.0.0.1. The human brain has an efficient, if not always accurate, autocorrect system. We don't always see the things that are written if they are very similar to, but different from, what we're used to seeing."}, {'account_id': 9162, 'date': '2015-05-29 03:28:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

I think is a suitable way to avoid confusion, regardless of whether or not we believe Debian *should* be doing this.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-05-29 13:03:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-29 16:08:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
Elaborate on warning message

The warning about removing 127.0.1.1 is potentially confusing
(at least it confused me) because 127.0.0.1 is well known
as the loopback address and it may not be apparent that the
warning is actually about a different IP, 127.0.1.1 which
is not as well known. This patch elaborates on the fact
that 127.0.1.1, not 127.0.0.1 must be removed from
/etc/hosts.

Change-Id: Ie358dde24fc07c98948075d97c981985f5c2694b
Closes-Bug: 1459825

commit_message:
Add launchpad tag used by "Report a bug"

"Report a bug" automatically populates bugs on launchpad with
information about the manual. This additional config setting
will allow "Report a bug" to automatically tag the bug with the
respective manual.

Add this for admin-cloud-rst like it was done for the other guides.

Also, decrease version number to 0.9, it's not a 1.0 release yet.

Change-Id: I4555cc28ef30527e4349da5c4928ba265a19bb23

commit_message:
Dell SC driver honoring folder name after volume creation.

The Dell SC driver was not honoring the volume folder name
after creation.  This has been changed so that find_volume
now checks the dell_sc_volume_folder for the requested volume
before doing a general search of the storage center.  In
either case if more than one volume is returned (two in
the dell_sc_volume_folder or two outside of that folder) then
an exception is thrown.

Also the dell_sc_volume_folder, dell_sc_server_folder and
dell_sc_ssn variables are no longer being passed arond.  They
are saved as part of the backend API object.

Tests have been updated.

Change-Id: I962ea3ed262d21deff65cdc8476939aab6ba07e2
Closes-Bug: #1449290

commit_message:
Fix Flavor Detail tbl in legacy Launch Instance

This patch fixes the misaligned rows of the Flavour Details table, on
the first tab of the legacy Launch Instance workflow.

Patch also changes the markup for the Networks tab, which relied on CSS
that this patch removes.

Change-Id: Ie2fcedb5a7a7f5b3d9ffffd4f245f7ec5ff5470d
Closes-Bug: 1443322

commit_message:
Fix TemplateDoesNotExist at manage/unmanage volumes

manage/unmanage template includes wrong templates:

project/volumes/volumes/_unmanage_volume.html
project/volumes/volumes/_manage_volume.html

it should be admin/volumes/... instead of project/volumes/...

Change-Id: Ic1b16077630b39b8a72e773c562de2c65a5a11c3
Closes-Bug: #1459625

[{'created': '2015-05-26 08:12:04.000000000', 'message': "Auto-delete queues were deleted on RabbitMQ failover

When RPC client starts listening to reply queue and got disconnected from RabbitMQ,
reply queue got deleted because it was marked as auto-delete and no more consumers
were present.

This fix replaces auto-delete with queue 1H expiration. So clients have
up to an hour to reconnect to RaqbbitMQ prior to server's reply gets lost

Adopted from Ic1a20c309ff90618f715f4034847e6e159c486e8
Co-Authored-By: Stan Lagun<slagun@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I9119ee7fa798918811044625271140fabd812651
Closes-Bug: #1349301
"}]
commit_message:
Auto-delete queues were deleted on RabbitMQ failover

When RPC client starts listening to reply queue and got disconnected from RabbitMQ,
reply queue got deleted because it was marked as auto-delete and no more consumers
were present.

This fix replaces auto-delete with queue 1H expiration. So clients have
up to an hour to reconnect to RaqbbitMQ prior to server's reply gets lost

Adopted from Ic1a20c309ff90618f715f4034847e6e159c486e8
Co-Authored-By: Stan Lagun<slagun@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I9119ee7fa798918811044625271140fabd812651
Closes-Bug: #1349301

commit_message:
Fix the wrong check when boot from volume

Now,when create a server booting from volume.It will
raise an unexpcted 'FlavorDiskTooSmall' error in some
case.

For example,use 1G flavor and a 2G bootable volume of
which the image is small than 1G.The error would be
occured.

Change-Id: If4d04340a82ec98de6f44c485dd8d683284d0f06
Closes-bug: #1457517

commit_message:
Ensure empty paths raise a value error

Empty paths should not be allowed to be set or
fetched or normalized so check for those and raise
an error when one is encountered.

Also add some basic test conditions that ensure
the normpath method raises when it should.

Change-Id: I7f7e6600f03c67376ba310ab231b2e33cd7528db

commit_message:
Start adding rejection policy prototype to executors (WIP)

It is often desirable to have an executor do something
else then queue up work when its workers are at capacity.

To start to support this we need to start defining and
adding support to the existing executors so that they accept
and respect a provided policy.

Experiment for http://bugs.python.org/issue22737

Change-Id: Ieac2f8c002a96f98cf93fbd3e92afbd4b13702e1

commit_message:
Use states.check_task/retry_transition in action(s)

Be more strict about our task and retry transition(s) and
call into the state transition checking function(s) to ensure
that we continue making valid transition(s) or die.

Change-Id: Ib016e787a9382d06d4a7c15298bbcaa9a3f80368

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: I55ec1908f330e8f106b4e4f8e2435b5135b22e85

This patch adds a file documenting the use of isolated networks with static
IP addresses. This optional functionality allows the use of static IP addresses
on networks based on function: Internal API, tenant, storage, storage management,
and external/public API.

Change-Id: I185c6d87cb4e84d7c58ac279b8e6609d876c82c9
Co-Authored-By: dprince@redhat.com

commit_message:
Document how to use network isolation/static IPs

This patch adds a file documenting the use of isolated networks with static
IP addresses. This optional functionality allows the use of static IP addresses
on networks based on function: Internal API, tenant, storage, storage management,
and external/public API.

Change-Id: I185c6d87cb4e84d7c58ac279b8e6609d876c82c9
Co-Authored-By: dprince@redhat.com

[{'created': '2015-03-04 13:36:00.000000000', 'message': 'Create iSCSI lio portals with right IPs and port

Currently lioadm helper creates portals with fixed IP addresses 0.0.0.0
and ::0 and also uses fixed standard port 3260 ignoring any store
configuration (iscsi_ip_address, iscsi_secondary_ip_addresses,
iscsi_port) from the configuration as it should.

This could lead to problems if a different port was defined in the
configuration as the target would be available only on 3260 and other
services would look for it at configured port.

With this fix we now create the right portals with the right port.

Change-Id: I77e8865b1f015a9fa155f2b4552a5d9c27f5e122
Closes-Bug: #1425875

commit_message:
Create iSCSI lio portals with right IPs and port

Currently lioadm helper creates portals with fixed IP addresses 0.0.0.0
and ::0 and also uses fixed standard port 3260 instead of using store
configuration (iscsi_ip_address, iscsi_secondary_ip_addresses,
iscsi_port) from the configuration as it should.

This could lead to problems if a different port was defined in the
configuration as the target would be available only on 3260 and other
services would look for it at configured port.

With this fix we now create the right portals with the right port.

Since now we pass list of ips and port to helpers cxt helper has also
been updated to use these parameters instead of going directly to the
configuration.

Change-Id: I77e8865b1f015a9fa155f2b4552a5d9c27f5e122
Closes-Bug: #1425875

commit_message:
Expand the vote range for governance

The voting configuration for governance produces a red-x and
green-check for +/-1 code reviews now, which is confusing to people
since they normally associate those icons with +/-2 votes.  This
change expands the vote range to include +/-2 but gives no one
permission to vote at those levels.  This should cause Code-Review
votes to appear as +/-1, while the NoOp function continues to
mean that +2 votes are not necessary.

Change-Id: I31adfe3c847d181809825e1030e8c165e67ae9aa

commit_message:
Simplify the check for whether a metric matches

The old way was more efficient if there were few dimensions on
the metric and lots of Alarm Definitions with different
dimension sets for a given tenant id and metric name, but that
is probably unlikely. The more common case will be one or two
alarm definitions per tenant id and metric name and more
dimensions on the metric. The new algorithm is faster for that
case since it doesn't create every possible combinations of
dimensions like the old algorithm

Change-Id: I183570d52c61f0a2932cf37c5c659a6c529b4bbb

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-11 14:33:43.000000000', 'message': "Hyper-V: Fixes cold migration / resize issue

Commit https://review.openstack.org/#/c/162999/ changed where the Hyper-V
VM configuration files are stored. The files are being stored in the same
folder as the instance. Performing a cold resize / migration will cause a
os.rename call on the instance's folder, which fails as long as there are
configuration files used by Hyper-V in that folder, thus resulting in a
failed migration and the instance ending up in ERROR state.

Hyper-V configuration files are stored in a subfolder of the instance's
folder (e.g.: C:\OpenStack\Instances\instance-000000b6\Virtual Machines).

This commit makes sure that Hyper-V configuration files are not being
moved during migration by skipping subfolders in the instance's folder.

Change-Id: I4874eed7d284fab241e4371e550a88270ca156f1
Closes-Bug: #1453835

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Fixes cold migration / resize issue

Commit 3e42c7ae3f7a9353834c8c9c4dc79ee39dd0783b changed where the Hyper-V
VM configuration files are stored. The files are being stored in the same
folder as the instance. Performing a cold resize / migration will cause a
os.rename call on the instance's folder, which fails as long as there are
configuration files used by Hyper-V in that folder, thus resulting in a
failed migration and the instance ending up in ERROR state.

Hyper-V configuration files are stored in a subfolder of the instance's
folder (e.g.: C:\OpenStack\Instances\instance-000000b6\Virtual Machines).

This commit makes sure that Hyper-V configuration files are not being
moved during migration by skipping subfolders in the instance's folder.

Change-Id: I4874eed7d284fab241e4371e550a88270ca156f1
Closes-Bug: #1453835

commit_message:
server-group-list support 'all_projects' parameter

Supporting 'all_projects' in server-group-list so that
admin users can list other tenant's server groups.

Change-Id: Ie50288464ebc6585590a1a74efa8804584771ebc
Closes-Bug: #1454523

commit_message:
Sort _get_new/deleted_set_ips responses in unittests

This fixes the test_set_members_adding/deleting_less_than_5 unit test
that breaks with a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED (see the bug report).

The test assumed that the _get_new/deleted_set_ips from
neutron.agent.linux.ipset_manager return elements in a particular order.
Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=1.

The fix refactors the test case to force sorted responses from
_get_new/deleted_set_ips during unittests.

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will
be addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: I8408365825ec1e97a83c2181f38ec1f9468df91e

commit_message:
Allow to remove second _send_reply() call

Added a new configuration option `send_single_reply` which allows to
send a single AMQP reply instead of two. This will reduce amount of RPC
calls and increase transport productivity.

The new behaviour is not compatible with the old logic, so isn't
backward compatible and disabled by default.

DocImpact
A new configuration option added.

Blueprint: remove-double-reply

Change-Id: Idab118b22163e734aca010f325cddfaec26bfa0f

commit_message:
[install-guide] Add repo for RHEL 7

In RHEL 7, add the rhel-7-server-optional-rpms repository
to resolve dependency on python-webob package.

Change-Id: Ifad3ab2f95c88fef592d668302c30993445d854c
Closes-Bug: #1451338

commit_message:
Don't assume project IDs are UUID format

Since Keystone has the ability to be deployed with an LDAP backend, we can't
guarantee that project IDs will always be UUID formatted. That change makes it
so that we attempt to convert project IDs to bytes before packing and if we
fail, pass the original project ID into the payload at the expense of a
slightly longer payload.

Change-Id: Id81ed23879ee7a9adeb50454ef0cb7acd13f1a0a
Related-Bug: 1459382

commit_message:
Don't assume group IDs are UUID format

When using the Fernet token provider to build a federated payload, we can't
assume that the group ID will always be a UUID format that we can convert to
bytes. This change makes the Fernet code smart enough to pass the original
group ID in the payload if it can't convert it to bytes.

Change-Id: I6d00902eb461c22aafd9cb5ca706b05bedefd37d
Related-Bug: 1459382

@Assaf, you suggest to buy easy test cleanup by selling operators a sanity_check rule that will fail for them while their system has all the needed components to actually run neutron agents.

In that way, neutron makes the platform that has an older ipset version look worse than it is in reality. Remember, sanity_check tool is executed on production nodes, not on test runners.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:54:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

My only problem with this patch is that we don't use ipsets in namespaces - security group rules are always in the "root" namespace.  In fact, I've been trying to remove the namespace argument from the ipset manager code - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/180327/ but am hung-up on the functional tests using it for testing :(

Is there any reason we can't just reverse the tests to use ipsets in the root namespace and jump into the namespace to send the packets?  Then we wouldn't need to do this check.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-29 18:41:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

[{'created': '2015-05-29 15:04:42.000000000', 'message': "Add sanity test for ipset in a namespace

Old ipset/kernel versions cannot properly use ipset in namespaces.
While we don't use ipset in namespaces in production code, we do
during functional testing. This patch adds a sanity check while will
be used to determine if the ipset tests should be run in a future

commit_message:
Add sanity test for ipset in a namespace

Old ipset/kernel versions cannot properly use ipset in namespaces.
While we don't use ipset in namespaces in production code, we do
during functional testing. This patch adds a sanity check while will
be used to determine if the ipset tests should be run in a future
patch.

The sanity check was run on both a new and old kernel/ipset.
The check properly succeeds or fails and cleans up all resources
in both cases.

Related-Bug: #1459855
Change-Id: I3f3d108df14f1583f558643c555a17ed3fd6ca5a

[{'created': '2015-05-29 22:25:30.000000000', 'message': 'Expand the vote range for infra-specs

The voting configuration for infra-specs produces a red-x and
green-check for +/-1 code reviews now, which is confusing to people
since they normally associate those icons with +/-2 votes.  This
change expands the vote range to include +/-2 but gives no one
permission to vote at those levels.  This should cause Code-Review
votes to appear as +/-1, while the NoOp function continues to
mean that +2 votes are not necessary.

Also extend the Council-Vote to +2, but similarly give no permissions
to use it so that council votes will appear as +1, -1, or red-x in

Change-Id: I042e6168334fb11291edbaed97b3ae2424218166
'}]
commit_message:
Expand the vote range for infra-specs

The voting configuration for infra-specs produces a red-x and
green-check for +/-1 code reviews now, which is confusing to people
since they normally associate those icons with +/-2 votes.  This
change expands the vote range to include +/-2 but gives no one
permission to vote at those levels.  This should cause Code-Review
votes to appear as +/-1, while the NoOp function continues to
mean that +2 votes are not necessary.

Also extend the Council-Vote to +2, but similarly give no permissions
to use it so that council votes will appear as +1, -1, or red-x in
the case of a -2 veto (the -1/green-check dichotomy would also
seem weird for similar reasons).

Change-Id: I042e6168334fb11291edbaed97b3ae2424218166

commit_message:
go: replace ghetto getpwnam with os/user

Parsing /etc/passwd was always goofy, but some stuff that came up when
googling "golang getpwnam" led me to believe this functionality just
didn't exist in the go standard library.

Then I ran across os/user a few days ago, which is exactly what's needed.

Change-Id: I937f0a1397c70dc3f7b5b77d939deb10d6c7c480

commit_message:
Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for service_get_by_host*

This patches remove the hard-code permission checks for db call
service_get_by_host_and_topic and service_get_all_by_host_and_binary.

There are elevated contexts in the code used to call those methods which
aren't removed in this patch. The elevated context will be cleaned up in
last step. This is safe if we forget removing some hard-code permission.

sorry to nag at the comment but +1 for now (see inside)'}, {'account_id': 2696, 'date': '2015-05-17 16:40:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Pete: re: the comment:

Is there a case where the result of whataremyips() is **not** used (only) to determine if a ring device is local to the server/machine on which the currently-executing process is running?

What is a service's address?

The only reason it's useful to return only the bind_ip, if it's specified and not "any", is to support more than one logical Swift node cohabitating on a server/machine that has all their IPs.  I don't think you'd ever see this in the Real World(tm), but it definitely helps the SAIO.

In the SAIO case, if you have the following devices in the ring (via my new vagrant-swift-all-in-one patch with EC_DISKS=8 and SERVER_PER_PORT=false; see https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one/pull/16 ):

 Devices:    id  region  zone      ip address  port  replication ip  replication port      name
              0       1     1       127.0.0.1  6016       127.0.0.1              6016      sdb1
              1       1     2       127.0.0.2  6026       127.0.0.2              6026      sdb2
              2       1     3       127.0.0.3  6036       127.0.0.3              6036      sdb3
              3       1     4       127.0.0.4  6046       127.0.0.4              6046      sdb4
              4       1     1       127.0.0.1  6017       127.0.0.1              6017      sdb5
              5       1     2       127.0.0.2  6027       127.0.0.2              6027      sdb6
              6       1     3       127.0.0.3  6037       127.0.0.3              6037      sdb7
              7       1     4       127.0.0.4  6047       127.0.0.4              6047      sdb8

(For the moment, pretend the ring above is a 3-replica ring and not an EC ring--though note that the Swift probe tests do not work with the replica rings having any disk count != 4.)

And then you have 4 object-replicators pretending they're running on different storage nodes that look like this when they start:

 Starting object-replicator...(/etc/swift/object-server/1.conf.d)
 Starting object-replicator...(/etc/swift/object-server/2.conf.d)
 Starting object-replicator...(/etc/swift/object-server/3.conf.d)
 Starting object-replicator...(/etc/swift/object-server/4.conf.d)

Each of those four object-replicators wants to only deal with "local" disks.  In the real world, intersecting the set of all IPs of the server on which the object-replicator is executing with the replication IPs of devices in the ring works fine.  But on the SAIO, even with unique IPs per "server", that's still insufficient because all the IPs would be in the result of whataremyips() (all 4 replicators would work on all 8 disks) or only 127.0.0.1 would be in it (no object-replicator would work on the 6 disks of the other 3 "servers".  In either case, incorrect behavior results.

Relevant code is swift.obj.replicator.ObjectReplicator.build_replication_jobs() where the result of whataremyips() is passed into a call to is_local_device().  Now, this used to work because the 1.conf.d stuff had a bind_port of 6010 and both "server 1" disks (sdb1 and sdb5) would have had replication_port set to 6010.  But in the above ring, note that the config's bind_port of "6016" alone is insufficient to show that "sdb5" (replication_port of 6017) is "local" to "server 1".  Actual replication HTTP requests work because in a one-server-per-port deployment, there is an object-server bound to 127.0.0.1:6016 (for sdb1) and 127.0.0.1:6017 (for sdb5).  But for the purposes of determining that those two ring device records are "local" to "server 1", the replication_port value and the server's config (/etc/swift/object-server/1.conf.d/*) is not enough.  The bind_ip needs to be taken into account, and that's what this patch does.

If a "server" has a "local" disk, then it must have an object-server process running on the same "server" to service replication, the object-server process whose IP and port is in the ring for that device as replication_ip and replication_port.  That object-server is either bound to exactly the ring device's replication_ip or to 0.0.0.0.  In the first case, that single IP can be leveraged to differentiate the disks between different "servers" even if all of those servers have IPs in the full list that whataremyips() with no args returns.  That's what we do for the SAIO.  In the second case, you don't differentiate, so the SAIO needs to **not** do that.  In a real deployment, it won't matter (you can have 0.0.0.0 bind_port values for your object-servers as long as the different nodes' whataremyips() results intersected with storage policy ring devices' replication_ips are disjoint).

Is there a better definition of "my" hiding somewhere in the above?'}, {'account_id': 2696, 'date': '2015-05-19 05:22:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Pete: please see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/184189/ for the real reason for this monkey business.'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2015-05-19 15:59:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I'm sorry that I made you type that missive. I think your log message explains everything perfectly as it is.

Also, confession time: I was so focused on "theoretically correct" way to compare IPv6 addresses, that I forgot that breaking out to C and using getaddrinfo() provides us with a convenient normalization. This is brilliant and purists can eat it.

I'm just going to re-upload the same thing with adjusted comment.'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2015-05-19 16:00:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-19 16:46:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Allow SAIO to answer is_local_device() better

Common SAIO setups have multiple "servers" all on the same host with
different ports for the different "servers" (which happen to match the
IPs specified in the rings for the devices on each of those "servers").

This breaks down if you want to set up the SAIO to have one
object-server per disk.

However, you can configure the SAIO to have different localhost IP
addresses (e.g. 127.0.0.1, 127.0.0.2, etc.) in the ring and in the
servers' config files' bind_ip setting.

This new whataremyips() implementation combined with a little plumbing
allows is_local_device() to accurately answer, even on an SAIO.

In the default case (an unspecified bind_ip defaults to '0.0.0.0') as
well as an explict "bind to everything" like '0.0.0.0' or '::',
whataremyips() behaves as it always has, returning all IP addresses for
the server.

Also updated probe tests to handle each "server" in the SAIO having a
unique IP address.

Change-Id: I7dfef9cc4a3c48145011d9d13d904e6b623de020

commit_message:
Alter governance repo voting rules

Restrict Code-Review votes to -1..+1, but allow anyone to leave
them.  This will allow direct binary feedback from both TC and
non-TC members on a change (currently, feedback from non-TC members
requires leaving a comment).  Make Code-Review votes not required
for a change to merge.  This means they are purely advisory.

Add a TC-Vote label and allow TC members to vote -1..+1 on this
label.  This will allow the formal tallying of TC member votes.
It is also not required (by Gerrit) since the actual rules are
complicated and no one thinks implementing them in prolog is
a good idea.  So we will simply rely on the chair to tally the
votes properly and execute the workflow or abandon operations
as appropriate.

Change-Id: I510bf1195d8af5d5c466fb05630ad6f9ec11b3e1

commit_message:
Use oslo.log instead of oslo.incubator log module

oslo.log has graduated from oslo-incubator, magnum need use oslo.log
instead of oslo.incubator log module.

NOTE: openstack.common.log registers its options at import time, but
oslo.log needs to call register_options() explicitly.

Change-Id: I671bb020b628bd972813daf5936040b7f1c6bf7a
Closes-Bug: #1459736

commit_message:
Make ansible more verbose in gate-wrap

We have a case where ansible is taking over an hour to excute
what appears to be moving a file. This patch adds -vvv to the
ansible execution commands to see if we can get more information
about what is happening during that hour.

Job Reference:
https://jenkins01.openstack.org/job/check-tempest-dsvm-full/822/console

Change-Id: I22f2c3b97378996be21943ae9f01d14e07d38e83

(2 comments)

@Jay, thanks for your review!

We want to make the v2 api back-compatible. It means if the api can't configured by policy rule, then add hard-code permission checks just make sure it match the behavior before.

The show method actually can be configured by policy rule, because the elevated context pass down to the db layer code. The elevated context make db layer hard-code permission checks useless.

So we needn't add hard-code permission for show method.

For v2.1 API, our goal is make the api configured by policy rule. so we needn't hard-code permission check at api layer also.

Thanks
Alex"}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2015-05-12 11:15:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

commit_message:
Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for service_get_by_compute_host

This patches remove the hard-code permission checks for db call
service_get_by_compute_host.

There are elevated contexts in the code used to call those methods which
aren't removed in this patch. The elevated context will be cleaned up in
last step. This is safe if we forget removing some hard-code permission.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part

Change-Id: I06c90564e32a89761b752782d3fb74da9cc4d343

commit_message:
Use os._exit after forking

As the docs point out(*), _exit should be used after a fork() to avoid
both processes flushing filehandles, calling destructors with side
effects, etc.  This change does just that.

(*) https://docs.python.org/2/library/os.html#os._exit

Change-Id: I68da6283c44ab8857baf217ac1443bd17988257d

commit_message:
Cleanup stale metadata processes on l3 agent sync

Currently l3 agent only cleans up stale namespaces.
The fix adds checking and deleting stale metadata processes
to NamespaceManager class responsible for clearing stale
namespaces

Change-Id: I2b081803e312589d3d8a7808d286a6c9827ef53f
Closes-Bug: #1455042

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: Ib78f3fe7535ab1d86f1311d33152d88b2dbf9d1f

commit_message:
Map Mysql to isolated networks

This change adds parameters to specify which networks the MySQL
service will use. If the internal_api network exists the MySQL
service will bind to the IP address on that network, otherwise
the services will default to the IP on the Undercloud 'ctlplane'
network.

This patch also drop the old 'controller_host' variable from
the puppet controller template since it is no longer in use.

Change-Id: I4fba2c957f7db47e916bc269fb4bd32ccc99bd4c

commit_message:
Use heat inputs for network port settings

This patch updates the controller and compute roles
so that we use get_input in the software configuration
instead of calling get_attr/get_param there.

Change-Id: I1dc11987b4ea3c37775b14fbdddb75588499e9bb

commit_message:
Bump ddt to min version 0.7.0

Manila and manilaclient projects use lib "ddt" for testing. Both use feature
of this lib that appeared only starting with version 0.7.0 [1]
It worked till that moment because latest version was installed each time.
But it can cause errors in theory if current version 0.4.0 will be installed
indeed.

[1]: https://github.com/txels/ddt/commit/c55bbf5d

Change-Id: Iea6881a5efc7e3203747603727bec51bf4a4c0d8

commit_message:
Bump oslo.vmware version to 0.13.1

oslo.vmware 0.13 now uses suds-jurko, instead of suds, which is
compatible with Python 3.

oslo.vmware 0.13 caused issues in nova, issue fixed in oslo.vmware
0.13.1.

This change prepares the work to drop the suds dependency.

Change-Id: I2fc039f6540b4a272f4e1abf3ea4e5240295e4c2

commit_message:
Add cli tests for --verify and friends

The tests that will change after the verify-always-true bug is fixed
are currently commented out.  The commented asserts show where we
want to go.

Also fixes --verify parser value

Change-Id: I891e3ead5fc3da3ed2ecba5d2befd9e910778655

commit_message:
Update sqlalchemy-migrate to 0.9.6

Nova code change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/153123/ makes the db migrate
operation fail with db2. Need to update sqlalchemy-migrate to 0.9.6 to solve
this problem.

Change-Id: I3ccdc9117a07135cea2f7be1c516838a287b5ac9
Related-Bug: 1428477

'}, {'created': '2015-05-26 09:01:21.000000000', 'message': "Don't create channel in RabbitMQ driver Connection.reset()

Current implementation of RabbitMQ driver in in Connection.reset() change
the channel to use and create a new channel for it. So it creates a new
channel after the each message send.

The Connection object works in a synchronous way. So only one channel
will be used at a time for one Connection object. So we can not close
the channel in reset().

Test test_connection_reset_always_succeed() removed, because we are not
create channel on reset().

Change-Id: Ie164840e6c055b01525b13aabdb8b9c7f5d1b98b
"}, {'created': '2015-05-27 07:37:36.000000000', 'message': "Don't create a new channel in RabbitMQ Connection.reset()

Current implementation of RabbitMQ driver in in Connection.reset() change
the channel to use and create a new channel for it. This happens after the
each message send.

There no big need to create a new channel each time, so we can cancel all
consumer queues, instead of creating a channel in reset().

Test test_connection_reset_always_succeed() removed, because we are not
create channel on reset() anymore.

Co-Authored-By: Mehdi Abaakouk<sileht@redhat.com>
Change-Id: Ie164840e6c055b01525b13aabdb8b9c7f5d1b98b

Change-Id: Ie164840e6c055b01525b13aabdb8b9c7f5d1b98b
"}]
commit_message:
Don't create a new channel in RabbitMQ Connection.reset()

Current implementation of RabbitMQ driver in in Connection.reset() change
the channel to use and create a new channel for it. This happens after the
each message send.

There no big need to create a new channel each time, so we can cancel all
consumer queues, instead of creating a channel in reset().

Test test_connection_reset_always_succeed() removed, because we are not
create channel on reset() anymore.

Co-Authored-By: Mehdi Abaakouk <sileht@redhat.com>
Change-Id: Ie164840e6c055b01525b13aabdb8b9c7f5d1b98b

[{'created': '2015-02-23 11:05:16.000000000', 'message': 'Scheduler: Introduce a FilterRequestSpec object

As part of Scheduler refactoring, we are planning to move all the data
request_specs dict to NovaObjects. This effort is about solidifying the
external interfaces of the scheduler component, in hopes of moving it
out of the Nova project.

This patch can be seen as a small step in that direction, for the
purpose of using a more object like interface in the scheduler code
(mostly filters at this point).

As a basic example: We have a need to detect if the request sent to the
scheduler related to an instance attempts to change the flavor. We add
this functionality as a method on an object that wraps the request_spec
dictionary, that we can now use in filter code to make decisions.

With this we get to iterate over the objects API while punting the work
of actually changing the RPC API to use new objects to a later series,
while avoiding the need to add messy functionality as utility methods that
deal with request_spec dictionaries that are on their way out.

Change-Id: I4bdcfc1df9d0ed9b64c41213cd4e0613a1ab6c88
Partial-bug: #1370390

commit_message:
Scheduler: Introduce a FilterRequestSpec class

As part of Scheduler refactoring, we are planning to move all the data
request_specs dict to NovaObjects. This effort is about solidifying the
external interfaces of the scheduler component, in hopes of moving it
out of the Nova project.

This patch can be seen as a small step in that direction, for the
purpose of using a more object like interface in the scheduler code
(mostly filters at this point).

As a basic example: We have a need to detect if the request sent to the
scheduler related to an instance attempts to change the flavor. We add
this functionality as a method on an object that wraps the request_spec
dictionary, that we can now use in filter code to make decisions.

With this we get to iterate over the objects API while punting the work
of actually changing the RPC API to use new objects to a later series,
while avoiding the need to add messy functionality as utility methods that
deal with request_spec dictionaries that are on their way out.

Change-Id: I4bdcfc1df9d0ed9b64c41213cd4e0613a1ab6c88
Partial-bug: #1370390

[{'created': '2014-03-12 17:36:59.000000000', 'message': 'Add an import whitelist helper factory

This patch adds a factory function for creating checks that allow
whitelisting imports in certain files.

The returned function can be registered as a pep8 check, and expects to
be passed the code to be used for the rule, a file to consider, and
whitelists of stdlib, 3rd party and project modules.

Unit tests that are part of this patch give an example of how this can
be used to create a function for a fictional Z123 rule that we can
register using pep8.register_check or as an entry point for flake8.

Change-Id: I61979d555fb2d551cdc0a02d41af8fd3e03247af

commit_message:
Add an import whitelist helper factory

This patch adds a factory function for creating checks that allow
whitelisting imports in certain files.

The returned function can be registered as a pep8 check, and expects to
be passed the code to be used for the rule, a file to consider, and
whitelists of stdlib, 3rd party and project modules.

Unit tests that are part of this patch give an example of how this can
be used to create a function for fictional rules Z123 and Z223, that we
can
register using pep8.register_check or as an entry point for flake8.

Change-Id: I61979d555fb2d551cdc0a02d41af8fd3e03247af

commit_message:
Match order of iptables arguments to iptables-save

The way we were forming our iptables rules was not matching
the output of iptables-save. This caused the logic that preserves
counters to miss many of the rules.

This patch corrects the order for the comments and the allowed address
pairs to match the output order of iptables-save.

Closes-Bug: #1456823
Change-Id: I34c2249d0865485578767865c82414e1d813d563
(cherry picked from commit 12889f70e1ae547598f4c663e9da5b9bb03e347e)

commit_message:
VMware: fill in instance metadata when resizing instances

Update instance metadata to the VMware resize spec. This is done by
updating the 'annotation' field. This enables an administrator
to search the VC according to values defined here.

Implemented blueprint vmware-driver-domain-metadata

Change-Id: I5794114e126a1bf0361e7035c40add8f7996468f

commit_message:
VMware: fill in instance metadata when launching instances

Add instance metadata to the VMware config spec. This is done by
updating the 'annotation' field. This enables an administrator
to search the VC according to values defined here.

Implemented blueprint vmware-driver-domain-metadata

Change-Id: Ia40fee366cab9ad99e276b0595fe0ad2972e54a9

commit_message:
Fix proxy delete error

I discovered with the functional tests that the delete proxy
was broken.  It should pass ignore_missing as a keyword argument
rather than positional.

Change-Id: I9281f5477a42428b301b2af019bb5ccc2684100d

Add relevant projects to $PROJECTS for akanda jobs

During akanda DSVM runs, add required projects to $PROJECTS to ensure
we have a local checkout of that code.

Change-Id: Ib33db6c1e6fae2023de81a85fb628458c562e038

commit_message:
Add Backend grading, and associated docs page

This adds a parameter to the backend class the defines its grade.
It can be overridden in the support-matrix.ini file it needed.

Change-Id: Icbcb3d88242c6d2de2c361722ddea85d4b585fca

commit_message:
Remove the no-parallel setting from pretty_tox.sh

pretty_tox.sh was setting --no-parallel, so even if you
wanted to be dangerous and live on the edge you couldn't.

This patch removest that limiter and let's you either:
 a. Run as many processes as you have nproc
 b. Specify how many processes you want by using
    "tox -- --concurrency=<n>"

Note that much past 6, things get a bit unstable.  Your
mileage may vary.  Gate appears to use 8, ran a sequence
of 10 iterations locally succesfully after modifying the
gluster tests. May be other gotchas out there though.

Change-Id: I593b8086f19c37a5abc55a23f92253706e100daf
Closes-Bug: #1459852
Parital-Bug: #1459854

commit_message:
Drop simplejson which was needed for Python 2.6

In 2.6 and earlier, the JSON module wasn't loaded as a C module, so it
was helpful to use simplejson if it was available. Since Python 2.6
support has been dropped in Kilo, remove the logic around simplejson.

Change-Id: I32f06b730d575ccf4770007aedf5e6902284d939

commit_message:
OVS_LIB support API for setting fail mode 'standalone'

The current API only support setting a bridge fail mode
to secure, this patch allow the user to set it to 'standalone'
as well

Change-Id: If7e6532dc7f8527c35834a37144ea4386fe1b861
Closes-Bug: #1458924

commit_message:
Remove appliance's hard-coded password in favor of ssh pub key

This removes the hard-coded password from the appliance VM's user-data
and replaces it with a SSH public key, which is read from a file whos
path is configured in rug.ini.

It also disables password logins for the user.  Another patch to
akanda-appliance-builder will allow developers to include a specified
debug user to allow debugging in dev environments.

Change-Id: I7db92bc7fd3743d89d73ab2a0b8da14685c30c69
(cherry picked from commit a06dbe7ab3d579c0c4cb84642ed1708d1442dc0b)

commit_message:
Fixing cue integration test gate

- Updated requirement.txt with accept libraries and versions
- Have DIB repo cloned by the devstack-vm gate
- Modify cluster test to test create, get, list and delete in one test
- Temporary disabled install of cue-dashboard until cloning issue
  is fixed

Change-Id: Ie5ffaf169d3915c4bd73d61ab05bfa8ac3f7f36b

commit_message:
Remove pretty_tox and use ostestr

This patch dumps pretty_tox.sh and gets Cinder on board
with using ostestr.  We're setting a concurrency value
of 6 (instances in the gate are 6 VCPU's), and things
seem to be stable at this value.

For folks running on 'smaller' system, it's still possible
to run in parallell > ncpu's but if there are problems you
can still specify concurrency in your tox argument.  Tox will
take the last occurence of the conncurrency argument; so for
example if you specify "tox -epy27 -- --concurrency=4" the
interpretted value for concurrency in the run will be 4.

Change-Id: I78c573367ffa1b2859c49e3ad6fcb4e586210f02

commit_message:
Reschedules sometimes do not allocate networks

Changes to instance.system_metadata weren't properly being saved
to the DB. The change to 'network_allocated' would be written to
the DB but not updated on the instance object. When the network
was cleaned up before a reschedule, the object would not notice
network_allocated' getting set to False, and not write the change
to the DB. After the reschedule, the instance would still have
'network_allocated' set to True, and skip allocating a network.
The node would go active with no network.

Since this is happening in the _allocate_network_async greenthread,
the solution is not to save in the async thread. The main thread
and the async thread share a reference to the same object and the
main thread waits for the async thread to finish before the final
save, so saving is unnecessary. I added comments on the
instance.save() calls that were part of the race so they don't get
removed or changed and reintroduce this bug.

Also, update the relevant test from mox to mock.

Change-Id: I937ec020b46703392bd603008d03af0f422bc0d1

commit_message:
Revert "Merge "Bootstrap variable overrides should only be default values""

This reverts commit 1fefd0f4259d670cea4075a7a3e52caeaab7ea9b, reversing
changes made to 74e6da9f4314a96b6d714c966699435316b4c075.

This patch incorrectly layers defaults in SCSS, which doesn't work. A
default does not override another default, so adding !default to our
overrides has caused them not to work.

Change-Id: I9f9c98262a428d84efe7887f76ff9e1af451c29b
Closes-Bug: 1459573

commit_message:
Provide Fedora support for StrongSwan

The initial release of StrongSwan VPNaaS driver only support Ubuntu.
This patch will provide the Fedora support. The different usage of
StrongSwan between Fedora and Ubuntu are:
- Uses 'strongswan' CLI command instead of 'ipsec'
- Configuration files location is different
- Strongswan.d directory in template directory does not include
  'charon' directory

Change-Id: I27d8518d1d8110453d4674a0c6fb3cb6072a32f0
Closes-bug: 1444776
Closes-bug: 1441788
(cherry picked from commit f8a62b09b60d60ce3aa4d841ef97ec1d003281e2)

I'll fix the typo in the commit message shortly. Jesse, this would require a new role, no?

Further, we need to at *least* include the bits in the container create role since the host's environment values will not carry through to the container. Anything the container may need to talk to the internet for over HTTPS with Python will need these variables. I agree the host portion is something deployers can use, but I'm not sure there's much point in only doing this for container creation if we're going to do it at all."}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-05-29 04:05:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

Looks good to me. For the case of upgrade we run setup-everything.yml to perform the upgrade which would call lxc-container-create.yml. when the container create play is called the container command execution is run which would pick up the changes in new and old containers. This should fulfill the upgrade case without having to create a new role that reruns parts that we're already accomplished in other tasks. If we could find a way to make this a role and use the meta dependency mapping I'd be for that however the container create process has a bit a of a chicken and egg problem because minimal packages must be present within the container to use ansible IE python. At this stage I'm for this change and it stands to solve the immediate problem of deploying osad behind a proxy."}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-05-29 08:25:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-29 08:25:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Verified

commit_message:
Handle proxies through environment variables

When running os-ansible-deployment on a cluster siting behind a proxy,
users may need to set up special variables for proxies so that pip, and
the services all work as expected.

Closes-bug: 1452456
Change-Id: I2a397abad6557a48bc737dcd9cca787fc5afa728

Perform sort when creating hostnames_ip file

commit_message:
Add tox target for bandit security checks

Bandit is produced by the OpenStack security team to do
static code analysis for security implementation failures.
It tests the code base for ~30 common security problems in
Python with more to come.

run with:
    tox -e bandit

Eventually we should have a check job that runs this target

Change-Id: I14c34c2ec8db73179964282cc95df96bd9a600fa

commit_message:
Set Rabbit recovery method for network partitions

Adds configurable option rabbit_cluster_partition_handling with default
value of pause_minority. Allows option to be explicitly set to ignore
through Ansible to reset to prior (and RabbitMQ default) behavior.

Change-Id: I52625390b388a55c6ed210b5804c7de336985f37
Closes-Bug: #1454860

commit_message:
Allow configuration of Nova SQLAlchemy options

Add variables for the following 3 nova.conf vars:
max_overflow (default 10)
max_pool_size (default 5)
pool_timeout (default 30)

This allows for sql tuning to better support bulk operations
(boot/delete) with the ability to define custom values in nova.conf
based on business needs.

Closes-Bug: #1447389
(cherry picked from commit 58212d9b8a7e692d49ae2852f349829355f93a2b)

Change-Id: I6f19c9e3a39979f6b78bdf86d9a06ce12aee7a7b

commit_message:
Fix dhcp _test_sync_state_helper asserting calls wrong

It was using a non-existing method that did nothing and
that masked other problems with the tests that used it.
Changed to use assert_has_calls() and fixed the problems
that fell out.

Change-Id: I4a64c3365f9958b14c2384932a31da2ce191e2e2
Closes-Bug: 1426265
