Removed use of contextlib.nested call from codebase, as it has been
deprecated since Python 2.7.

There are also known issues with contextlib.nested that were addressed
by the native support for multiple "with" variables. For instance, if
the first object is created but the second one throws an exception,
the first object's __exit__ is never called. For more information see
https://docs.python.org/2/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.nested
contextlib.nested is also not compatible with Python 3.

Multi-patch set for easier chunks. This one addresses the tests from
neutron/tests/unit/api directory.

Line continuation markers (e.g. '\') had to be used or syntax
errors were thrown. While using parentheses is the preferred way
for multiple line statements, but in case of long with statements
backslashes are acceptable.

Partial-Bug: 1428424
Change-Id: I09673f9d4c7f07d3043804676fef018905dd1239
'}]
commit_message:
Remove use of contextlib.nested (api-tests)

Removed use of contextlib.nested call from codebase, as it has been
deprecated since Python 2.7.

There are also known issues with contextlib.nested that were addressed
by the native support for multiple "with" variables. For instance, if
the first object is created but the second one throws an exception,
the first object's __exit__ is never called. For more information see
https://docs.python.org/2/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.nested
contextlib.nested is also not compatible with Python 3.

Multi-patch set for easier chunks. This one addresses the tests from
neutron/tests/unit/api directory.

Line continuation markers (e.g. '\') had to be used or syntax
errors were thrown. While using parentheses is the preferred way
for multiple line statements, but in case of long with statements
backslashes are acceptable.

Partial-Bug: 1428424
Change-Id: I09673f9d4c7f07d3043804676fef018905dd1239

commit_message:
Clean up temporary images during dockerctl backup

Images created for backup should be cleaned up to
conserve disk space on Fuel Master and reduce
the size of future backups.

Change-Id: I4adf06219bc1edfd97e7cb8ce350d1da47fd9ba3
Closes-Bug: #1437245

commit_message:
Defer creation of router JSON in get_routers RPC

The get_routers method in the l3 RPC code has a log.debug
statement that formats all of the router data as indented
JSON. This method can be expensive if there are hundreds
of routers being synced and it happens even if debugging
is disabled since the function call result is the parameter
to the debug statement.

This patch adds and leverages a small helper class that takes a
callable and its args and defers calling it until the __str__ method
is called on it when it's actually trying to be rendered to a string.

Change-Id: I2bfceb286ce30f2a3595381b62bdc6dd71ed8483
Partial-Bug: #1445412
(cherry picked from commit 649599457e29b58ad0aec9ace990e0a2b59b05d0)

commit_message:
Handle no ofport in get_vif_port_to_ofport_map

Newly added ports to OVSDB might not yet have an
ofport number assigned to them. This causes the
return from the DB query to return a list instead
of a port number.

This patch handles that by attempting to convert
each result into an integer and then catching the
exception and continuing through the iteration to
ignore uninitialized ports like these.

It also adds a unit test based on data from a
failure observed in the gate.

Change-Id: I5c1bc8363cc7b07a03df12e3ccd49a09b1907ad2
Closes-Bug: #1444269
(cherry picked from commit e7e2609fae70dbffa0ddbf37c7804587e216648c)

commit_message:
A Default CLI plugin

A plugin that can be used by default by any CLI application. This would
allow us to convert the other service CLIs to a consistent set of
options.

Closes-Bug: #1459478
Change-Id: I9ce6c439d530040e9375f7fd26a9ec2e0ba8b2a4

commit_message:
fix network setup on evacuate

As reported in bug #1430042 when using evacuate + neutron virtual
machines fail to evacuate because of a failure to update port
bindings.  A similar issue applies to FloatingIP setup for
nova-network.

A related fix was proposed in
https://answers.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/nova/+question/257358
and seemed to be fixing users.

This handles things a bit differently in order to more cleanly
use existing code.

Change-Id: Iafa6d2e9eb76ea0389067c939f21ac2181df6f95
Closes-Bug: #1430042
(cherry picked from commit 7c81be3c2952f26e30bb8394c8e2803d31fc3b26)

commit_message:
Fix disk image create errors behind proxy

This commit fixes errors while trying to create a
DIB ramdisk with ironic-agent element when built
behind proxy. It fixes the issue by making it install
latest versions of pip and setuptools which has the
fixes for them.

Change-Id: I1ffb832ebab009b2d77a46e6c8fc758dd9632359
Closes-Bug: 1449852

commit_message:
Block allowed address pairs on other tenants' net

Don't allow tenants to use the allowed address pairs extension
when they are attaching a port to a network that does not belong
to them.

This is done because allowed address pairs can allow things like
ARP spoofing and all tenants attached to a shared network might not
implicitly trust each other.

Change-Id: Ie6c3e8ad04103804e40f2b043202387385e62ca5
Closes-Bug: #1447242
(cherry picked from commit 927399c011409b7d152b7670b896f15eee7d0db3)

commit_message:
Match order of iptables arguments to iptables-save

The way we were forming our iptables rules was not matching
the output of iptables-save. This caused the logic that preserves
counters to miss many of the rules.

This patch corrects the order for the comments and the allowed address
pairs to match the output order of iptables-save.

Closes-Bug: #1456823
Change-Id: I34c2249d0865485578767865c82414e1d813d563
(cherry picked from commit 12889f70e1ae547598f4c663e9da5b9bb03e347e)

commit_message:
Add policy to cover snapshotting of volume backed instances

This change adds a policy that can be configured to limit or prevent the
snapshotting of volume backed instances.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Id5486f3bb18c6431c4ae8def6540ba780ea15b0a

Cleanup minor rubocop offenses

Cleaned up all the minor rubocop issues, the ones left relate to
complex logic and what I think is a bug in rubocop for nested
vs compact modules/class definitions.

commit_message:
Process port IP requests before subnet requests

When a port requests multiple fixed IPs, process the requests
for specific IP addresses before the ones asking for a subnet.
This prevents an error where the IP that was requested happens
to be the next up for allocation so the subnet request takes it
and causes a DBDuplicateEntry.

Closes-Bug: #1459467
Change-Id: I645565c7fe0c47c58d686b25020bb49a0b9089f5
(cherry picked from commit 817b45b6406d9730859535ac54d73ec5c85451d0)

A little late to join the review party .. but here I am!

1) Would you please re-introduce service_type. Do not eliminate it because controversial. I would like to see it as a fixed set of strings with CRUD for the same. The idea being that we can register multiple Load Balancers, Firewall implementations etc and we can search from available device types based on this field.

2) Please add for device_template a field to indicate vendor. Perhaps a vendor-id pointing to a table of Vendors.
CRUD for the same.

3) While key-value dictionary is a nice catch all .. where we know we need some fields, please let us specify them. Like 1 & 2.
Would also like to have in a device_template "device_type" which takes a value of "Physical" or "virtual". To your comment of physical topology, if it is Physical, the geo for purposes of physical topology would come from the physical device itself backing this device. If Virtual, from the compute-node hosting the given device VM.

As part of sanity testing the data we would check that one or the other is specified. In the case it is virtual, we then verify that either an image-id is provided, or a volume-id is provided, need to further specify "source-type" which takes on Image/Volume and the source-id is then interpreted as an image-id or a volume-id. Bob had made a comment to this effect in patch-1 and seems to be lost in patch-2.

4) the management URI may itself be a VM image that needs to be launched, which then gets an address. And it would then establish a workflow where it needs to be spun up first, before any of its children devices can be launched.

5) In Isaku's google doc slides where he talks of single versus multiple RPC queues for control of these devices .. might be say that it applies regardless of the device being physical or virtual? We have not covered this option in this spec. At the very least default it to one type for now and extend it later?

My reasoning for specifying some fields -- Far easier than ploughing through a dictionary of key-value pairs.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-22 23:37:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

Thank you for the review.
At first, this spec is not for the final version. But for minimul one for routervm plugin.
After having working version with neutron routervm plugin,
the api discussion would be resumed and api will be modified.

Let me clarify the requests.

> 1)
Unfortunately there have been so many objections.
At least the name, 'service_type', needs to be changed because Neutron has service type framework and service type is already used for different meanings. Do you have any candidate?

> 2)
I'm neutral.
Do you want vendor table instead of vendor string row?

3a) device_type
I agree that a kind of necessity of a way to distinguish physical from virtual.
But I'd like to postpone the discussion on requirements for physical because even in physical device case, it provides virtual(or logical) services. I'd like to focus on virtual router as the simplest use case.

3b) key-value
I think what you want is CLI option something like create-template --nova-command-line ...
which automatically invokes nova cli parsar and produces a list of key-value pair.

Do you have any idea on sanity checking? 
Unfortunately even nova client and nova api layer check arguments in very easy way.

4)
A new driver will be needed to handle such special behavior.
Something like NovaDriverForSuchDevice(NovaDriver) which fullfills mgmt uri.

5)
Such discussion is postponed for future because it isn't needed for routervm reference implementation which uses provider network."}, {'account_id': 10182, 'date': '2014-07-29 01:13:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Malini,

Regarding the service_type (or service_whatever) and the possibility for multiple implementations: for sure a service like Neutron will have multiple implementations of say firewalls or load balancers. But I don't see why that implies a need for a service_type in tacker. Each implementation (probably a driver in a neutron service plugin) must keep track of which devices (and indirectly device templates) in can, or already have, place(d) services instances in. commit_message:
Process port IP requests before subnet requests

When a port requests multiple fixed IPs, process the requests
for specific IP addresses before the ones asking for a subnet.
This prevents an error where the IP that was requested happens
to be the next up for allocation so the subnet request takes it
and causes a DBDuplicateEntry.

Closes-Bug: #1459467
Change-Id: I645565c7fe0c47c58d686b25020bb49a0b9089f5
(cherry picked from commit 817b45b6406d9730859535ac54d73ec5c85451d0)

commit_message:
Adds database population to sles;opensuse

The install guid for sles and opensuse based systems
lacks information how to populate the database.
This fix adds the corresponding command.

Change-Id: I590d64f363925a81d20fa94a88a065e38c55f0a5
Closes-Bug: #1460046

commit_message:
Remove _ensure_flush() from SSYNC receiver

The Receiver._ensure_flush() method in ssync_receiver.py has
the following comment:

    Sends a blank line sufficient to flush buffers.

    This is to ensure Eventlet versions that don't support
    eventlet.minimum_write_chunk_size will send any previous data
    buffered.

    If https://bitbucket.org/eventlet/eventlet/pull-request/37
    ever gets released in an Eventlet version, we should make
    this yield only for versions older than that.

The reference pull request was included with eventlet 0.14 [1] and
swift now requires >=0.16.1 so it is safe to remove _ensure_flush()
and save > 8k bytes per SSYNC response.

[1] https://bitbucket.org/eventlet/eventlet/commits/4bd654205a4217970a57a7c4802fed7ff2c8b770

Change-Id: I367e9a6e92b7ea75fe7e5795cded212657de57ed

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-27 15:52:10.000000000', 'message': "Make SSYNC receiver return 5xx when initial checks fail

The ssync Receiver performs some checks on request parameters
in initialize_request() before starting the exchange of missing
hashes and updates e.g. the destination device must be available;
the policy must be valid. Currently if any of these checks fails
then the receiver just closes the connection, so the Sender gets
no useful response code and noise is generated in logs by httplib
and wsgi Exceptions.

This change moves the request parameter checks to the Receiver
constructor so that the HTTPExceptions raised are actually sent
as responses. (The 'connection close' exception handling still
applies once the 'missing_check' and 'updates' handshakes are in
progress.)

Moving initialize_request() revealed the following lurking bug:
 * initialize_request() sets
       req.environ['eventlet.minimum_write_chunk_size'] = 0
 * this was previously ineffective because the Response environ
   had already been copied from Request environ before this value
   was set, so the Response never used the value :/
 * Now that it is effective (a good thing) it causes the empty string
   yielded by the receiver when there are no missing hashes in
   missing_checks() to be sent to the sender immediately. This makes
   the Sender.readline() think there has been an early disconnect
   and raise an Exception (a bad thing).

The fix for this is to simply make the receiver skip sending the empty
string if there are no missing object_hashes. A test is added that verifies
the protocol completes end-to-end when there are no missing_checks
(test/unit/obj/test_ssync_sender.py:TestSsync.test_nothing_missing).

Change-Id: I036a6919fead6e970505dccbb0da7bfbdf8cecc3

no useful response code and noise is generated in logs by httplib
and wsgi Exceptions.

This change moves the request parameter checks to the Receiver
constructor so that the HTTPExceptions raised are actually sent
as responses. (The 'connection close' exception handling still
applies once the 'missing_check' and 'updates' handshakes are in
progress.)

Moving initialize_request() revealed the following lurking bug:
 * initialize_request() sets
       req.environ['eventlet.minimum_write_chunk_size'] = 0
 * this was previously ineffective because the Response environ
   had already been copied from Request environ before this value
   was set, so the Response never used the value :/
 * Now that it is effective (a good thing) it causes the empty string
   yielded by the receiver when there are no missing hashes in
   missing_checks() to be sent to the sender immediately. This makes
   the Sender.readline() think there has been an early disconnect
   and raise an Exception (a bad thing), as revealed by
   test/unit/obj/test_ssync_sender.py:TestSsync.test_nothing_to_sync

The fix for this is to simply make the receiver skip sending the empty
string if there are no missing object_hashes.

Change-Id: I036a6919fead6e970505dccbb0da7bfbdf8cecc3

commit_message:
Make SSYNC receiver return a reponse when initial checks fail

The ssync Receiver performs some checks on request parameters
in initialize_request() before starting the exchange of missing
hashes and updates e.g. the destination device must be available;
the policy must be valid. Currently if any of these checks fails
then the receiver just closes the connection, so the Sender gets
no useful response code and noise is generated in logs by httplib
and wsgi Exceptions.

This change moves the request parameter checks to the Receiver
constructor so that the HTTPExceptions raised are actually sent
as responses. (The 'connection close' exception handling still
applies once the 'missing_check' and 'updates' handshakes are in
progress.)

Moving initialize_request() revealed the following lurking bug:
 * initialize_request() sets
       req.environ['eventlet.minimum_write_chunk_size'] = 0
 * this was previously ineffective because the Response environ
   had already been copied from Request environ before this value
   was set, so the Response never used the value :/
 * Now that it is effective (a good thing) it causes the empty string
   yielded by the receiver when there are no missing hashes in
   missing_checks() to be sent to the sender immediately. This makes
   the Sender.readline() think there has been an early disconnect
   and raise an Exception (a bad thing), as revealed by
   test/unit/obj/test_ssync_sender.py:TestSsync.test_nothing_to_sync

The fix for this is to simply make the receiver skip sending the empty
string if there are no missing object_hashes.

Change-Id: I036a6919fead6e970505dccbb0da7bfbdf8cecc3

commit_message:
Fix test_opts to not resolve requirements

Glance py27 tests are broken because test_opts loads the
entry_points and resolves the deps. Some deps (I think
stevedore's) conflicts with pbr 1.0.0 which released
recently.

This patch loads the entry_points with require=False.

Change-Id: I0f36faa60a4688c8aba5e31f69e3f1818adb681a
(cherry picked from commit 99826d08d4c48cb83f4c5eb7fc79bba9ffd86f41)

commit_message:
Renamed climate.conf to blazar.conf

Now Blazar uses as default config file blazar.conf. For backward
compatibility the old config file (climate.conf) is still supported, but
the values of blazar.conf taking precedence.
Updated some doc files to reflect this change.
Updated manually the tools/config directory.

Change-Id: I0c35a0d9508f76072b5510513f2f1ef83fb50fd6
Partial-Bug: #1311761

commit_message:
Integrating Blazar to Horizon

This is the first patch to integrate Blazar to Horizon.
The code is in Blazar client to avoid dependency issues (when the client
changes, our Horizon integration should change accordingly)
This integration is installed as new package called blazardashboard.

Change-Id: Ia65713550fe2b8caa321e204805ecccc3096cc2f
Implements: bp/climate-dashboard

commit_message:
Blazar Client support for API V2 version

Adding v2 package to climate client and also modifying the current
base client in order to support V2 operations.
Adding version discovery to Blazar client.

Partially implements: climate-client-v2
Change-Id: I995bdea717d0eddba47b8c5a091239be318387b7
Co-Authored-By: Pablo Andres Fuente <pablo.a.fuente@intel.com>

commit_message:
Modify endpoint for multiple version support

Modifying the reservation endpoint being registered on keystone
to support multiple version handling. The problem was that the
endpoint contained a hardcoded API version that needs to be
removed when v2 version usage is needed.
Partially implements: blueprint climate-client-v2

commit_message:
Fix exceptions on pep8 check due to missing tempest.conf

* Don't read the test config when the config module is imported
* Don't instantiate clients when the client module is imported

Change-Id: Ie56ad28c1bd1911eb8fb964cf7384a71745f8606

Dear Igor Degtiarov,
    The self.gnocchi_archive_policy_data is a dict rather than a string. You can find the class GnocchiDispatcher in which  gnocchi/ceilometer/dispatcher.py file. The function of _load_archive_policy used to get the return data that is a dict. The dict data source form the policy_config_file which named gnocchi_archive_policy_map.yaml, maybe likes follow:
cat gnocchi_archive_policy_map.yaml

# This file is used to map a metric name to corresponding archive policy
# and used by the ceilometer dispatcher.
# Format: <metric_name>: <policy>

cpu_utils: "high"
disk.*: "low"

Your previous comment: as the above, we want to traverse a dict's elements, which using the items() method is appropriate in my mind, and using iterator is also OK.

By the way, if self.gnocchi_archive_policy_data is {} or None {}, the expression "self.gnocchi_archive_policy_data is not None" always is True.

Thank you! :)'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-05-28 08:31:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I don't see any bug fix here. This changes the format of the yaml file from:

  ---
   - foo.*: low
   - bar.*: high

to:

  foo.*: low
  bar.*: high

The original format preserve the order, the new one doesn't. Why do you want to change it to ?"}, {'account_id': 8358, 'date': '2015-05-28 10:05:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Dear Mehdi Abaakouk (sileht),
    I really don't want to and don't change the original format of gnocchi_archive_policy_map.yaml(https://github.com/openstack/gnocchi/blob/master/etc/ceilometer/gnocchi_archive_policy_map.yaml) file. 
    Please look up above comments. 
    [1]According to gnocchi_archive_policy_map.yaml file and the function of _load_archive_policy, you known that self.gnocchi_archive_policy_data will seem like {'foo.*': 'low', 'bar.*': 'high'}. 
    [2]Then, the focus is the line code "for metric, policy in enumerate(self.gnocchi_archive_policy_data):" , and the key is enumerate() that get 'metric' is a integer(like 0,1,2...). When fnmatch.fnmatch(metric_name, metric) will report that "oslo_messaging.notify.dispatcher TypeError: object of type 'int' has no len()". It's obvious that int(metric is) has no len()!
    [3]Because of the miss about order that add archive_policy_file to the conf and generate the GnocchiDispatcher instance in the test_ceilometer_dispatcher.DispatcherTest.test_archive_policy_map_config, we cann't find this bug through unit test.
    [4]So I fix the unit test as well, and "tox -e py27  test_ceilometer_dispatcher.DispatcherTest.test_archive_policy_map_config" is succeeded.

Did you have a test about it? Indeed, I'm not sure this is a bug, but after I have done above source code changes, it is running well on which my test bed.'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-05-28 15:18:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Remove is_public from domain layer

The pre-reserved attribute 'is_public' has been removed from the
api layer, this patch will remove it from the domain layer and add
an unit test for that.

Closes-Bug: #1452447

Change-Id: Ie75088d95e7e0ae53df5290b33f3a184adc22239

The way we deal with running commands on the booted guest is a real mess, as has been observed every time a change like this is proposed. Some calls use /bin, some use /sbin, and most don't use an absolute path at all. So lacking a more robust solution where there could be a way to say how a particular image should be interacted with, I am ok with the path part. Attila's comment about the 'set' options concern me but since we only test on cirros I don't really see a better way to make sure nothing goes unexpectedly wrong."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-29 14:23:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Verified

commit_message:
Extend PATH and set -o pipefail in linux ssh

Some distributions have 'ip' utility in /sbin, and there's no link with target of /bin/ip
(CentOS7, for instance).
By this patch we
1) remove redundant specification: /bin is in PATH already
2) add /sbin to PATH, since SSH misses it by default
3) "set -eu -o pipefail" to make errors more explicit

Change-Id: I7693911e6b883a21baafe6f804564754ebaea5e0

commit_message:
Fix requirement conflict with flake8.

flake8 ==2.4.0 is incompatible with hacking, both 0.10.0 or 0.10.1
hard depend on 2.2.4, so we need a range until hacking has done
another release.

Change-Id: I1ad37d6c88b7b9fe50138f3248c609bfe8a5a123

commit_message:
Remove extra return value from scenario call to show_router

This was missed in the client-returns-one-value work. It was not noticed
because the bad code is inside a conditional on CONF.network.public_network_
which is not set by gate jobs.

Hi, Dave, as my understand this is pretty close to AggregateMultiTenancyIsolation except 'reserved_pool' hint, is it right? Is there any possible we extend 'AggregateMultiTenancyIsolation' to support that?

For any new filter, we should add describe at here https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/doc/source/devref/filter_scheduler.rst

Thanks
Alex"}, {'account_id': 1882, 'date': '2015-05-05 10:45:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Alex,

The main difference between this filter and the AggregateMultiTenancyIsolation filter is that the existing filter will return all possible hosts for a tenant while my filter will return either those hosts in the aggregate OR those not in it. Meaning if a tenant wants to use the aggregate (indicated by the hint) and the aggregate is full they will not get a host. But it also means if they don't specify the hint they can be sure their instance will NOT go to the aggregate. I thought this differed enough form the existing filter to warrant a new filter.

I will push a new patch with the description.
Thanks,
Dave"}, {'account_id': 1882, 'date': '2015-05-05 13:01:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2015-05-05 13:06:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I agree with Alex, I think you should work on supporting isolating tenants for the existing AggregateMultiTenancyIsolation filter

FYI a spec was created for Juno but neither approved nor implemented, but I liked the approach. Since filters no longer require a spec, you can just take the idea and work on the implementation.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/99476/5'}, {'account_id': 1882, 'date': '2015-05-05 13:54:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

An important part of this proposal is the ability for a user/tenant to specify if they want to use the aggregate or not if we tie that functionality to the existing filter I worry it starts to overload it's function. For example in a situation where we follow the old proposed spec and the default configuration is used even if a tenant specifies the hint to target an aggregate they may still end up outside of that aggregate. The alternative is making the hint the final decider in whether or not only the aggregate is used which removes a level of control from the cloud operator."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-05 20:27:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Create a reserved aggregate filter

This reserved aggregate filter only allows certain tenants to use hosts in
an aggregate that has been marked for their use. If a request has the
scheduler hint 'reserved_pool' the host will be selected if it is marked
with the tenant's id. If the hint is not present the host will not be
selected if it is marked with any tenant id, including the one in the
request. This has will allow tenants to have reserved hosts to use for a
specific purpose. The tenant may chose to put an instance in their
reserved pool or not - hence the hint.

Change-Id: I5aa8362293c88f9e10e1b9be8a02da4f2d0bc8f1
Implements: blueprint reserved-aggregate-filter

Make 'gate-murano-devstack-dsvm' non-voting

This patch is required to resolve circle dependencies to fix
stable/juno branch. Currently it's broken.

Patch, that is needed to be merged, after this fix will be merged:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/184196/

After that tests should pass here:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/183101/

ToDo: After stable/juno will work again, this commit would be reverted.

Change-Id: I6c873273807242d4b7fc160a6e0032af341fb446
Closes-Bug: #1452930

commit_message:
Added MySql reconnect and better error output

Better exception handing so that our exceptions don't get eaten with a general
GeneratorExit exception.

Attempt reconnect to MySQL under the assumtion that the connection timed out.

Change-Id: Ia1daa5cfb397fb2fb9c8f9bc07e99adba435ae38

commit_message:
virt: make sure convert_all_volumes catches blank volumes too

convert_all_volumes would skip over blanks. This patch makes sure it
will consider them now too.

The patch (42ea00ee) that introduces the method for some reason
completely missed the Blank volume type.

Closes-bug: #1451950

Change-Id: I146a9bb09c149db1bab6dc13c082b00e5de8b764

commit_message:
Fake missing local_gb for root_device_hint plugin

At the first run of discovery, the RAID volumes might be missing from
the node. To avoid the standard plugin erroring, root_device_hint plugin
fakes the missing local_gb value. The fake value will be overwritten
with the correct one during later runs.

Change-Id: I2d38557fa356656e44e9915d3c4a5abb9cf1731d

[{'created': '2015-05-29 01:55:33.000000000', 'message': 'Fix ansible-playbook segfault

ansible-playbook segfaults when we supply the "-I" option to pip.

commit_message:
Fix ansible-playbook segfault

ansible-playbook segfaults when we supply the "-I" option to pip.
Remove this option since it's also slowing down our run. See related
bug for more details.

Closes-Bug: 1459801
Change-Id: Idaf090d642c5e0ab5e143d824ca99f9d39679d87

commit_message:
Configure computes after controllers

Sometimes it causes problems when nova-compute is started before
nova-conductor. The nova-compute service doesn't register itself with
nova API and it loops these messages in the log:

2015-05-18 12:46:41.466 4085 WARNING nova.conductor.api [req-f72df90b-8e66-4e8b-8ec0-ba6362b83e61 - - - - -] Timed out waiting for nova-conductor.  Is it running? Or did this service start before nova-conductor?  Reattempting establishment of nova-conductor connection...

Nova-compute never recovers from this state unless manually
restarted. This causes the deployment to fail. To prevent this issue
from happening, we make the compute node configuration happen after
controller nodes have been configured.

Change-Id: I790e1d9f6c325af885edc86e5caa66a19398e712
Co-Authored-By: Jason Guiditta <jguiditt@redhat.com>

[{'created': '2015-05-28 12:53:25.000000000', 'message': "py34: don't run any tests except unit tests

py34 job was intended for unit tests only. It's important to distinguish
between different types of tests, because they all have different
requirements to execution environment. E.g. functional tests are not
expected to run in a restricted env designed for unit tests, and that's
even more valid for fullstack tests.

Otherwise, the job may fail or apply irrecoverable changes to test
runner system, breaking the system.

If we ever want to support py3 for other types of tests, we should add
separate jobs just for that.

Note that the neutron-python3 blueprint was not intended to introduce
changes to support anything but unit test execution with the new Python
version, so strictly speaking, any effort to make other test types work
is out of scope.

Change-Id: Ia96f03f05269c1938b51ee26f4b4075b69967bb8
"}]
commit_message:
py34: don't run any tests except unit tests

py34 job was intended for unit tests only. It's important to distinguish
between different types of tests, because they all have different
requirements to execution environment. E.g. functional tests are not
expected to run in a restricted env designed for unit tests, and that's
even more valid for fullstack tests.

Otherwise, the job may fail or apply irrecoverable changes to test
runner system, breaking the system.

If we ever want to support py3 for other types of tests, we should add
separate jobs just for that.

Note that the neutron-python3 blueprint was not intended to introduce
changes to support anything but unit test execution with the new Python
version, so strictly speaking, any effort to make other test types work
is out of scope.

Change-Id: Ia96f03f05269c1938b51ee26f4b4075b69967bb8

commit_message:
Remove simplejson from staticweb

Since we're dropping Python 2.6 support, we can rely on stdlib's json
and get rid of our dependency on simplejson.

This lets us get rid of some redundant Unicode encoding. Before, we
would take the container-listing response off the wire,
JSON-deserialize it (str -> unicode), then pass each of several fields
from each entry to get_valid_utf8_str(), which would encode it,
(unicode -> str), decode it (str -> unicode), and then encode it again
(unicode -> str) for good measure.

The net effect was that each object's name would, in the proxy server,
go str -> unicode -> str -> unicode -> str.

By replacing simplejson with stdlib json, we get a guarantee that each
container-listing entry's name, hash, content_type, and last_modified
are unicodes, so we can stop worrying about them being valid UTF-8 or
not. This takes an encode and decode out of the path, so we just have
str -> unicode -> str. While it'd be ideal to avoid this, the first
transform (str -> unicode) happens when we decode the
container-listing response body (json.loads()), so there's no way out.

Change-Id: I00aedf952d691a809c23025b89131ea0f02b6431

- do not mention Nova plugin (it is internal Nova framework to add new
  functionality), instead mention nova-compute service

  with vCenter we just run nova-compute (VCDriver) on Controller nodes,

commit_message:
Remove mentioning of "Nova plugin" and Controller and Compute mixture

- do not mention Nova plugin (it is internal Nova framework to add new
  functionality), instead mention nova-compute service
- in Fuel it is not possible to combine Controller and Compute roles,
  with vCenter we just run nova-compute (VCDriver) on Controller nodes,
  but it does not mean that we are combining Compute and Controller
  roles.

Change-Id: I4cf5c8295cd1cd7a0acf265d6709f22ac008683e

commit_message:
Deprecate auth.identity.v3.federated module

Rename the plugins, as we usually use ``federation` module instead of
``federated``. Also the stub class was renamed from
``FederatedBaseAuth`` to ``FederationBaseAuth``.

Module ``auth.identity.v3.federated`` has deprecation warning added.

Change-Id: I411c1dc4fc2ce80249f7071398ea4002422dc1be
Partially-Implements: bp refactor-federated-plugins

commit_message:
Apply a list_image_members rule of GET to image client

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the part
of the rule to image client.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I67c284bf1882c178fc25e9978a723289a86c4d56

subject: Apply a show_image rule of GET to clients

commit_message:
Apply a show_image rule of GET to clients

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the part
of the rule to image/compute clients.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I08a0a0e9f11fa6c225404cac63c0541dd345e77c

commit_message:
IBP: configure mcollectived to NOT daemonize on Ubuntu

sys v init scripts are inherently racy since creating a PID file takes
a while. In particular collectived needs about 0.6 seconds to daemonize
itself and create its PID file. If the service gets restarted in this
interval the second instance of the daemon gets started without stopping
the previous one. Apparently mcollectived gets restarted very often during
the final phase of IBP. Hence get rid of sys V init script and use
upstart job to manage mcollectived.

Merge-After: https://review.fuel-infra.org/7093
Closes-Bug: #1454741
Change-Id: Ie74539a068f33c485573645e6a2f88bd0972b59b

commit_message:
Split up and improve speed of keygen tests

test_generate_keypair is nova's slowest unit test, partly because it's
doing 3 separate things, and partly because we're generating
unnecessarily large keys which can suffer from entropy problems.

This patch splits up the 3 cases and asks for a 1024-bit key instead of
4096.

Change-Id: I7516b63e2b49251d44b4206b565a34bc7ccc6539

commit_message:
Adds neutron-server and agents as pacemaker resources

Adds neutron-server, neutron-l3-agent, neutron-dhcp-agent,
neutron-openvswitch-agent and neutron-metadata-agent  as
pacemaker resources.

Change-Id: I4dcc6f56db4c27a2a4f627fa8303cbeb2bd563d4

commit_message:
nailgun-agent: use service command to restart mcollective

mcollectived can be launched via upstart job or systemd unit.
Fortunately the service command hides those gory details.

[{'created': '2015-05-27 13:55:16.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Pass '--dhcp-authoritative' option to dnsmasq"

This reverts commit ed799e38fe740621776aab51c95ec1db248af997,
Which introduced a regression[1].
A fix for the DHCPNAK after neutron-dhcp-agent restart issue[2]
can be found here[3]

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1457900
[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1345947
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185486

Change-Id: I64d236f41e5941abe53aac9319a2ac7b2d94c39c
'}, {'created': '2015-05-27 15:34:01.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Pass '--dhcp-authoritative' option to dnsmasq"

This reverts commit ed799e38fe740621776aab51c95ec1db248af997,
Due to an introduced a regression[1]:
In case where neutron was configured to have more than one DHCP agent per
network (dhcp_agents_per_network<=2), dnsmasq rejects leases of others
dnsmasq instances. The NACKs came from dnsmasq caused instances to stuck
in the network boot for long time. regression scenario:
1. Set dhcp_agents_per_network=2 option in neutron.conf
2. Set up two or more different nodes with enabled neutron-dhcp-agent
3. Create a neutron network with --enable-dhcp option
4. Create instance with that network

The the reverted commit originally came to fix the issue[2] with DHCPNAKs sent
after neutron-dhcp-agent restart:
A Restart of the neutron-dhcp-agent service, caused dnsmasq logs start flood:
DHCPNAK ... lease not found.
DHCPNAK is replied by dnsmasq for all DHCPREQUEST renews from all VMs, However
the MAC and IP pairs exist in host files.
The reason behind this is that upon restart, dnsmasq forgets about all 
leases (since it runs with leasefile-ro option).
This results a small network downtime when client tries to renew its lease.

An alternate solution for this can be found here[3].

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1457900
[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1345947
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185486

Change-Id: I64d236f41e5941abe53aac9319a2ac7b2d94c39c

commit_message:
Revert "Pass '--dhcp-authoritative' option to dnsmasq"

This reverts commit ed799e38fe740621776aab51c95ec1db248af997.

Due to an introduced a regression[1]:
In case where neutron was configured to have more than one DHCP agent per
network (dhcp_agents_per_network<=2), dnsmasq rejects leases of others
dnsmasq instances. Some clients do not check server-id for those NAKs,
failing to set an address.

The reverted commit originally came to fix the issue[2] with DHCPNAKs sent
after neutron-dhcp-agent restart. This issue is expected to be fixed by a
separate patch[3].

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1457900
[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1345947
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185486

Related-Bug: 1457900
Related-Bug: 1345947
Change-Id: I64d236f41e5941abe53aac9319a2ac7b2d94c39c

Use new docker exec call

Docker-py would soon deprecated the execute method, instead
they suggest to use exec_start and exec_create

refer: http://docker-py.readthedocs.org/en/1.2.2/change_log/#120

Closes-Bug: #1454847

commit_message:
Save iptables after flushing during cloud-init

The iptables rules should be saved after being flushed as part of the
cloud-init process. If the reboot plugin is used, the default CentOS
rules are loaded on boot because we are not saving the cleared set of
rules. This can cause some network configurations to break.
Ubuntu is not impacted as they do not have any 'default' rules.

Change-Id: I49842cd833a736f318dd237f07be2267dbfb27ab
Closes-Bug: 1459733

[{'created': '2015-05-28 07:08:11.000000000', 'message': "Persist DHCP leases to a local database

Due to issues caused by dnsmasq restarts sending DHCPNAKs,
change Ieff0236670c1403b5d79ad8e50d7574c1b694e34 passed the
'dhcp-authoritative' option to dnsmasq. While this solved the
restart issue, it broke the multi-DHCP server scenario because
the dnsmasq instances will NAK requests to a server ID that
isn't their own.

Problem DHCP Request Lifecycle:

Client: DHCPDISCOVER(broadcast)
Server1: DHCPOFFER
Server2: DHCPOFFER
Client: DHCPREQUEST(broadcast with Server-ID=Server1)
Server1: DHCPACK
Server2: DHCPNAK(in response to observed DHCPREQUEST with other Server-ID)
          ^---Causes issues

This change removes the authoritative option so NAKs are not
send in response to DHCPREQUEST's to other servers. To handle
the original issue that Ieff0236670c1403b5d79ad8e50d7574c1b694e34
was inteded to address, this patch also allows changes to be persisted
to a local lease file.

to another agent, a fake lease file is generated for dnsmasq to start
with. The contents are populated based on all of the known ports for
a network. This should prevent dnsmasq from NAKing clients renewing
leases issued before it was restarted/rescheduled.

commit_message:
Persist DHCP leases to a local database

Due to issues caused by dnsmasq restarts sending DHCPNAKs,
change Ieff0236670c1403b5d79ad8e50d7574c1b694e34 passed the
'dhcp-authoritative' option to dnsmasq. While this solved the
restart issue, it broke the multi-DHCP server scenario because
the dnsmasq instances will NAK requests to a server ID that
isn't their own.

Problem DHCP Request Lifecycle:

Client: DHCPDISCOVER(broadcast)
Server1: DHCPOFFER
Server2: DHCPOFFER
Client: DHCPREQUEST(broadcast with Server-ID=Server1)
Server1: DHCPACK
Server2: DHCPNAK(in response to observed DHCPREQUEST with other Server-ID)
          ^---Causes issues

This change removes the authoritative option so NAKs are not
send in response to DHCPREQUEST's to other servers. To handle
the original issue that Ieff0236670c1403b5d79ad8e50d7574c1b694e34
was inteded to address, this patch also allows changes to be persisted
to a local lease file.

In order to handle the issue where a DHCP server may be scheduled
to another agent, a fake lease file is generated for dnsmasq to start
with. The contents are populated based on all of the known ports for
a network. This should prevent dnsmasq from NAKing clients renewing
leases issued before it was restarted/rescheduled.

Closes-Bug: #1457900
Change-Id: Idc91602bf8c474467e596cbd5cbaa8898952c841
(cherry picked from commit 4aba83fd22c8880a2d24f27e43a32cc164abe3e0)

commit_message:
Rename discoverd -> inspector

As agreed on the summit I'm renaming the python modules
and doing some adjustments:
* This is a breaking change, so version is bumped to 2.0.0
* Used this chance to split conf options over proper sections
* RELEASES.rst is gone; it's too hard to keep it up-to-date;
  anyway git does better job at doing history
* Dropped deprecated option ports_for_inactive_interfaces
* Dropped old /v1/discover endpoint and associated client call
* No longer set on_discovery and newly_discovered in Node.extra
  (deprecated since 1.0.0, superseded by the get status API)
* Default firewall chain name is "ironic-inspector" and
  is configurable

Notes:
* Some links will be updated after real move.
* Stable branches will probably use the old name.
* Some usage of discovery word is left in context of
  "discovered data"
* DIB element will probably be deprecated, so leaving it
  alone for now.
* Some usages of word "discovery" in the README will be updated
  later to make this patch a bit smaller
* Ramdisk code will be moved to IPA, so not touching it too much

Change-Id: I59f1f5bfb1248ab69973dab845aa028df493054e

commit_message:
fix neutron l3 with wrong admin_user param

in cluster/manifests/neutron/l3.pp
we define cluster::neutron::l3 with param $admin_username = 'neutron'
but at line 48
fuel call $admin_user instead of $admin_username

The purpose is to set $admin_user to $admin_username

Change-Id: I05533735cfb747a4ca8c75783b410131f4689c2e
Closes-Bug: 1405730

commit_message:
fix neutron dhcp with wrong admin_user param

in cluster/manifests/neutron/dhcp.pp
we define cluster::neutron::dhcp with param $admin_username = 'neutron'

but at line 43
fuel call $admin_user instead of $admin_username

The purpose is to set $admin_user to $admin_username

Change-Id: I608fbaafddca6271663664126bf3788766c2da64
Closes-Bug: 1405735

Fix hashmap_thresholds table for postgres

Ensure uniq names for UniqueConstraint on
table hashmap_thresholds this is needed for
postgres.

I'm not quite clear about this. Starting from a normal git cloned tempest dir, can you say how it would be divided, and what OS_TOP_LEVEL would point to? Thanks."}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2015-05-06 10:17:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

When cloning tempest, you have .testr.conf in the root folder, and then a subfolder called tempest with all (most of) the code in it.
In that case OS_TOP_LEVEL is the default "./".

This change is to support the case where tempest is installed in a virtual environment. 
In that case tempest code will be deployed into a subfolder of lib/ in the virtual env, e.g. /opt/venvs/tempest/lib/python2.7/site-packages/tempest.
Because we do not have a tempest binary yet, to run tempest in that case I will have do:
- check out .testr.conf in my working folder, e.g. /opt/stack/tempest
- set OS_TOP_LELVEL to /opt/venvs/tempest/lib/python2.7/site-packages/tempest
- set OS_TEST_PATH to /opt/venvs/tempest/lib/python2.7/site-packages/tempest/test_discover'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2015-05-06 16:56:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

@Andrea: thanks for the explanation. There is a similar issue with distro packages that I solved by using a tempest symlink in the "working" directory.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-05-06 19:03:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm not sure this is something we want to do. (at least for right now) It seems like you already have to execute a bunch of manual steps to make this useful. I really think instead of trying to hack in running tempest with testr from a remote place we should be looking at solving the separation of run time and install time for the general case. There is a proposed summit session on this right now, so I think we should table this until that direction is set. 

We might also require some testr changes to better support this use case. Just adding another env var doesn't really seem like the right solution until everything is sorted."}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2015-05-06 19:11:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Matt: I agree with you that both this and the symlink thing are hacks. This cannot really do any harm, but we can certainly wait. I didn't think  there was a lot of interest in making most of tempest a "shared library" but perhaps there is now.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-05-17 06:53:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Why not name the variable as `TEMPEST_DIR`? This name used in devstack.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-05-29 10:15:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
Add OS_TOP_LEVEL to testr conf

When installing tempest, it could be that the root of tempest code
is not a subfolder of the folder where the testrepository
configuration is held, and where test results are stored.
unittest2 will refuse to run tests for which the discovery root
is not a subfolder of the specified top level folder.

To fully support this scenario, adding OS_TOP_LEVEL in .testr.conf
and defaulting it to "./" which is the current value.

Change-Id: I60f788051d6a10ab00aecef5d09093a68f7f4030

commit_message:
Revert "Pass '--dhcp-authoritative' option to dnsmasq"

This reverts commit 74a16fde1c9972dc3c5d07215ca9d5e8f2e23d70.
Due to an introduced a regression[1]:
In case where neutron was configured to have more than one DHCP agent per
network (dhcp_agents_per_network<=2), dnsmasq rejects leases of others
dnsmasq instances. Some clients do not check server-id for those NAKs,
failing to set an address.
The reverted commit originally came to fix the issue[2] with DHCPNAKs sent
after neutron-dhcp-agent restart. This issue is expected to be fixed by a
separate patch[3].
[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1457900
[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1345947
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185486
Related-Bug: 1457900
Related-Bug: 1345947

Change-Id: Iabe8b94302a8add6fe3f8d5eb3830234de0323e8

commit_message:
Fix ovs agent restore local_vlan_map failed

when ovs agent restart, it will restore the local_vlan_map, but in
some condition, if a device does not be set tag in ovsdb, the function
'db_get_val("Port", port.port_name, "tag")' will return a empty list,
it does not need 'provision_local_vlan' for this device.

Change-Id: I70ed30e6ea5d13e6f14bb41c957320cc21dbca1b
Closes-bug: #1458709

commit_message:
Only have one path of support for api-metadata

The current cookbook allows the enabled_apis nova.conf key
to include the metadata value.  This causes the nove compute
service to try to auto start the api-metadata service.  But we
also have the api-metadata recipe in the run list by default which
also tries to start the api-metadata service. This can cause timing
issues with the starting service.

This patch will remove the metadata value from the enabled_apis
attribute, and put out a warning if it's included.  The api-metadata
receipe should be used to control this service.  By default the
api-metadata recipe is included in the os-compute-api role which
is included in the os-compute-single-controller role. So, in most cases
it's already included in the run list.

Change-Id: Ief1a98cf2ab072a8aa892c65c5fc07d12a02722c
Closes-Bug: #1415220

commit_message:
Improve `clear_expirer_metering_data` for SQL

Backport/rewrite `https://review.openstack.org/#/c/96489/`
from Juto to Icehouse.  Allows bulk deletes, instead of
looping through the different rows.  Takes care of mapping
the old `sourceassoc` table, not present in Juno.

Closes-Bug: 1289166

Change-Id: I86ecb40a1951ec9ca30a3ff38ffa90b1f4a00e96

[{'created': '2014-11-20 19:29:41.000000000', 'message': 'Containers Service Spec

Containers share many features in common with Nova instances. For the common
features, virt drivers for Nova can be used to surface basic instance
functionality. For features that go beyond what can be naturally fit within
a virt driver, we propose a new API service that allows for advanced features
to be added without conflating the worlds of instances and containers.

Re-post of the spec originally posted at:
https://review.openstack.org/114044

Change-Id: Ic5d95f5d6ba0d6845023bf59f9bad4377d50578f
'}]
commit_message:
Containers Service Spec

Containers share many features in common with Nova instances. For the common
features, virt drivers for Nova can be used to surface basic instance
functionality. For features that go beyond what can be naturally fit within
a virt driver, we propose a new API service that allows for advanced features
to be added without conflating the worlds of instances and containers.

Re-post of the spec originally posted at:
https://review.openstack.org/114044

It'll now be in there twice :) Please don't do this."}, {'account_id': 8213, 'date': '2015-04-28 19:50:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Matthew is right, Bartosz, you're still the author of the commit, there is no reason to add yourself as a Co-Author to this commit. See author:

    Bartosz Fic
<bartosz.fic@intel.com>Nov 17, 2014 1:04 PM

Which means, the co-author line should be removed, since it has no use.

Also, it's funny that the commit message has 2 cherry picked from commit lines (one from master, one from Juno).

Also, this hasn't merged in Juno yet, so -1 remains until then."}, {'account_id': 12814, 'date': '2015-04-29 08:06:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-29 09:04:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

It has 2 cherry pick lines because the commit message of the commit it is cherry-picked from itself contains a cherry-pick line :) Specifically, this is a cherry pick of the juno backport, which you rightly noted hasn't merged yet, not of the original commit. The reason for that is that the conflicts are the same, so there is no use resolving them twice in potentially subtly different ways.

Incidentally, I've seen various approaches to this. It would be nice to have an agreed convention. I obviously like this one :) If we say that we always append to the original commit message, the most recent is at the bottom. If there had been additional conflicts in the second backport, they would be underneath the second cherry-pick line."}, {'account_id': 8213, 'date': '2015-05-01 14:35:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Matthew, yeah, I figured that out, it is not the first time I've seen commit messages like this. :)

And I also agree with your opinion and I think it can be useful for other reviewers. For example, it would be better to compare this commit to the one in Juno, rather than just figure out all the differences / what happened between this commit and the one on master.

Anyways, commit is still in review in Juno."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-11 17:06:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. This isn't a security fix and it's not probably a critical fix, but this filter is broken by default without this simple change (the original unit tests were pretty bad for this filter, along with whatever testing people were doing on it out of tree).

Given the change is the same as what's on stable/juno and it's trivial, and the filter is broken by default without this, I'm OK with getting this in before icehouse is end of life."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-28 17:31:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
Type conflict in trusted_filter.py using attestation_port default value

When trusted filter (nova/nova/scheduler/filters/trusted_filter.py)
in nova scheduler is running with default value of attestation_port:

default='8443'

method _do_request() in AttestationService class has this line:

action_url = "https://%s:%d%s/%s" % (self.host,
self.port, self.api_url, action_url)

It is easy to see that default type of attestation_port is string.
But in action_url self.port is required as integer (%d).
It leads to conflict.

This change provides more tests than is required only to cover this bug
fix. This cases are testing AttestationService _do_request() method
using different status_codes and different texts returned by mocked
request method.

(cherry picked from commit fdcf358eaeef6edb5c8d2dcc94f906a22882544a)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/unit/scheduler/filters/test_trusted_filters.py

Tests aren't in tests/unit/.

Use jsonutils from nova.openstack.common instead of oslo.utils.

(cherry picked from commit b251958e61a62aea7facea574e7aca366af4b004)

Closes-Bug: #1381468
Change-Id: I1ad57b5bd1986360416948fd00dec22456dc29a7

commit_message:
Heat could not create samples with Ceilometer

Heat could not create samples with Ceilometer, because ceilometer client has
change some key words in CREATION_ATTRIBUTES which is using by create sample.

Change-Id: I8e8dc80ae1b666ae74e2b2c2b757e7f468c25de2
Closes-Bug: #1455421

commit_message:
Update port security group, relevant ipset member can't be updated

There is only 1 member named p1 in sg1.And 1 member named p2 in sg2.
The sg2 can access sg1.So p2 can access p1.
After p1 updated to sg3, and sg1 removed p1 from ipsets. But when sg
update the ipsets, it can get the sg1 ip is none,and the logical exe
set_members when exist ip in sg1,but now p1 had removed from sg1,so
sg2 won't updated.

Change-Id: Ib301d1d08ed7df14ba56ff7e9862be5b37e17481
Closes-bug:#1458786

commit_message:
rhel-common element should not use attach with activation key

In the case of using portal registration with an activation key, the
rhel-common element is still executing a `subscription-manager attach`
command. This should not happen if an activation key is provided. This
is because an activation key already provides the subscriptions to
attach.

This patch fixes this behavior.

Change-Id: I5a8425d1778362bb7a0dadc91a46308f16b2a526
Closes-Bug: #1456648

commit_message:
Save snapshot to db before stack snapshot complete

When executing stack snapshot heat do not release stack lock
some undefined amount of time because it needs to prepare
some data for stack snapshot. It leads to situation when stack
snapshot is complete(from user perspective) but nobody can do any
operations with stack. So the fix executes snapshot saving to DB
right before stack becomes complete.

Change-Id: Id011142498fee49fee9ec1437fc0816b25780e48
Closes-bug: #1456672

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: If51059c31c82d5235e2ae21143911b5561783ca6

commit_message:
Move guestagent settings to default section

The guestagent related settings are in the database section of the
taskmanager.conf.sample file.  If a user were to use this sample then
the guestagent related settings will not be read by the taskmanager
service because it expects these guestagent related settings to be
in the default section.  This fix moves the guestagent related
settings to the default section.

Change-Id: I8dbdf7abcfd5f2341831cc6daaf5cb14d8d42d61
Closes-Bug: #1459415

Polling task creation is extended to aggreagate the project filters
coming from different pipelines for the same task.
Compute pollsters are extended to poll data from the requested projects only.
Publishing part of the pipeline is also extended to filter the
samples coming from the polling tasks based on the pipeline specific
project config. This is necessary as a polling task polls data for
multiple pipelines and those multiple pipelines can have different
project config.

Implements blueprint project-based-data-collection-configuration

Change-Id: I8e6987108968fe95068d8f82ff1b1daff4f8b994
'}]
commit_message:
Adds project based filtering for compute pollsters

Polling task creation is extended to aggreagate the project filters
coming from different pipelines for the same task.
Compute pollsters are extended to poll data from the requested projects only.
Publishing part of the pipeline is also extended to filter the
samples coming from the polling tasks based on the pipeline specific
project config. This is necessary as a polling task polls data for
multiple pipelines and those multiple pipelines can have different
project config.

Implements blueprint project-based-data-collection-configuration

Change-Id: I8e6987108968fe95068d8f82ff1b1daff4f8b994

commit_message:
Introduce interface changes for project based data collection

It extends source in decoupled pipeline with projects parameter.
The projects parameter is split into include_projects and exclude_projects
based on the possible negation in the input.

Mixing normal and negated project ids in a single pipeline is rejected.

Pollster interface is extended with the project filter from the pipeline.

Implements blueprint project-based-data-collection-configuration

commit_message:
Adding stepped deployment to devtest_overcloud.sh

Adds initial support for stepping through a deployment using heat
hooks/breakpoints.

Currently only works with puppet implementation for nomergepy templates
and requires the following:

- latest release of python-heatclient, e.g including:
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/173969/
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/179196/
- Recent heat, e.g including:
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/177961
- This t-h-t patch adding an environment used by this patch:
    https://review.openstack.org/161927

When you have all those in place, simply add --with-steps to enable
stepped deployment.

Change-Id: I6a83d5a3c1dde1cbcc2a9d70cfc7b74c4bec079f

commit_message:
Use correct time delta function

The .seconds attribute of a timedetla object cannot be taken in
isolation because it can overflow into days. For example, a -1 second
difference will become -1 day and 86399 seconds.

This became a problem when the agent clock was slightly ahead of
the server clock. When calling (server_time - agent_time).seconds
in this scenario, it would go below 0 in the daily seconds and
wraparound to 86399 seconds and -1 day.

This patch corrects the issue by using a method in timeutils that
ends up calling total_seconds(), which was designed for this usecase.
It also restores the formatting that was removed in patch:
Ibfc30444b7a167fb18ae9051a775266236d4ecce

Closes-Bug: #1456760
Change-Id: Ie90249ab68bb5f8d117872d52180c7087d8fac9b

commit_message:
Allocation Pool should display a full text help

Steps to reproduce:

1. Network Detail -> Create Subnet.
2. Fill out necessary info, then navigate to Subnet Detail page.
3. Hover the mouse on the allocation pool help.
4. You will notice the tooltip can't display the full text.

Root cause is that tooltip is not using word-wrap: break-word.

Change-Id: I2664e8d6ea76bdc37b5f67499761860d8fa390cb
Closes-bug: 1458088

commit_message:
Allow for default() filters for jinja variables

The custom checking for undefined variables was incorrectly considering
a variable that uses a default filter as being undefined. A default
filter allows for providing a default value for an otherwise undefined
variable, and thus it should be allowed to pass through the initial
parse. This newly added regex will find default filter usage and allow
it.

Change-Id: I58991b30221036600f4c0cea7ae5473a5e439573

commit_message:
Remove python-qpid-proton from amqp1 reqs

python-qpid-proton is an transitive dependency for the amqp driver. The
real dependency is pyngus. In fact, python-qpid-proton is not even
listed in the global-requirements. This patch removes it from the amqp1
requirements.

Change-Id: I9f3854e0ee3b37b324f9932e7f42e37e7eb1c128

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-21 00:41:49.000000000', 'message': "Stop decoding object content

Previously, we had urllib3 (via requests) automatically decode all
responses with a Content-Encoding of deflate or gzip. This included
object downloads, which would in turn cause etag or content-length
mismatch errors. (See bug 1338464)

This was apparently added in response to a third-party proxy sitting
between the client and server which, having observed that the client
would accept gzip-encoded content while the server sent an unencoded
response, would perform the compression. (See bug 1282861)

Now, rather than having urllib3 perform the decoding, we'll do it
ourselves, and only for API requests where we want Python objects out
instead of raw bytes. Delfate support is dropped, as there are
apparently conflicting implementations.

In addition, a Cache-Control: no-transform header is added for object
downloads to discourage proxies from encoding otherwise unencoded
content. (See RFC 7230, Section 5.7.2)

Change-Id: I6cc30a5c12e37de06d7322533a3c36ad15397cc8
Closes-Bug: 1338464
Related-Bug: 1282861
"}, {'created': '2015-05-21 01:15:27.000000000', 'message': "Stop decoding object content

downloads to discourage proxies from encoding otherwise unencoded

Change-Id: I6cc30a5c12e37de06d7322533a3c36ad15397cc8
Closes-Bug: 1338464
Related-Bug: 1282861
"}, {'created': '2015-05-22 06:38:35.000000000', 'message': "Stop decoding object content

Previously, we had urllib3 (via requests) automatically decode all
responses with a Content-Encoding of deflate or gzip. This included
object downloads, which would in turn cause etag or content-length

This was apparently added in response to a third-party proxy sitting

Now, we'll no longer let requests send any default headers, nor do any

commit_message:
Stop decoding object content

Previously, we had urllib3 (via requests) automatically decode all
responses with a Content-Encoding of deflate or gzip. This included
object downloads, which would in turn cause etag or content-length
mismatch errors. (See bug 1338464)

This was apparently added in response to a third-party proxy sitting
between the client and server which, having observed that the client
would accept gzip-encoded content while the server sent an unencoded
response, would perform the compression. (See bug 1282861)

Now, we'll no longer let requests send any default headers, nor do any
decoding.

Change-Id: I6cc30a5c12e37de06d7322533a3c36ad15397cc8
Closes-Bug: 1338464
Related-Bug: 1282861

commit_message:
Modify deploy_cluster_wait method

- Add ability not to run services check after deployment
because in some cases like node deletion some services
are not gonna work

Change-Id: I3d179b6a8c6133200d87a139c9a0a000d5a97379
Closes-Bug: #1459704

commit_message:
Fixing Ceilometer platform test for Neutron notifications

Ceilometer test failed without any messages if all IP
addresses were allocated on external network. In addition,
some Neutron resources were not removed when the test failed.
This patch fixes these both issues.

Closes-Bug: #1459323
Closes-Bug: #1459326

Change-Id: I641f5fcf34f466ba2461680bf5b88b874ee3e38b

commit_message:
Add --tags option to stack-create and stack-update

Add ability to create stacks with tags and ability to update the tags
associated with a particular stack.

Examples:
  heat stack-create --tags=tag1,tag2 ...
  heat stack-update --tags=tag1,tag2 ...

blueprint stack-tags

Change-Id: I821a7291126fba9ec8d508480abf5a08718771ac

[{'created': '2015-05-21 17:05:39.000000000', 'message': 'Check volume_backend in retype

The retype command will always attempt a call
to the driver.retype method.  In *most* cases this
will hit the default impl which returns False because
most drivers don't implement any retype (most, a few do).

The problem is that the drivers that do implement this in
most cases will iterate through the settings and just make
the changes that are valid and ignore the rest, and then
return True. I think this is "ok" for the drivers to do,
drivers should be allowed to be somewhat dumb WRT Cinder
state management and placement info.  If we give them an
invalid command (which we're doing here) then it's on us
higher up the chain IMO.

The result is that for example if you're trying to retype
from backend-a to backend-b and backend-a implements retype
it can return True telling the manager that the volume was
succesfully retyped, even when it wasn't.

There's a lot of confusion around this bug, YES the
filter scheduler is used to determine if the retype is
valid and to what host.  That's not the issue, the issue
is that regardless of the source and destination host settings
that are provided from the filter-scheduler, we always make the
call to the driver, introducing the opportunity for a false
success status being reported back.

This patch adds a very simple check between the source and
destination host settings as provided by the scheduler and in
the case that the two are "different"(not including pool designations)
we skip calling the driver.retype method altogether and fall through
to the migrate process.

This introduces a new hosts_are_equivalent method in
cinder.volume.utils

Conflicts:
	cinder/volume/utils.py

Closes-Bug: #1452823
(cherry picked from commit bbb83aff023c90cfc186459603320ad3c622a40b)

commit_message:
Check volume_backend in retype

The retype command will always attempt a call
to the driver.retype method.  In *most* cases this
will hit the default impl which returns False because
most drivers don't implement any retype (most, a few do).

The problem is that the drivers that do implement this in
most cases will iterate through the settings and just make
the changes that are valid and ignore the rest, and then
return True. I think this is "ok" for the drivers to do,
drivers should be allowed to be somewhat dumb WRT Cinder
state management and placement info.  If we give them an
invalid command (which we're doing here) then it's on us
higher up the chain IMO.

The result is that for example if you're trying to retype
from backend-a to backend-b and backend-a implements retype
it can return True telling the manager that the volume was
succesfully retyped, even when it wasn't.

There's a lot of confusion around this bug, YES the
filter scheduler is used to determine if the retype is
valid and to what host.  That's not the issue, the issue
is that regardless of the source and destination host settings
that are provided from the filter-scheduler, we always make the
call to the driver, introducing the opportunity for a false
success status being reported back.

This patch adds a very simple check between the source and
destination host settings as provided by the scheduler and in
the case that the two are "different"(not including pool designations)
we skip calling the driver.retype method altogether and fall through
to the migrate process.

This introduces a new hosts_are_equivalent method in
cinder.volume.utils

Conflicts:
	cinder/volume/utils.py

Closes-Bug: #1452823
(cherry picked from commit bbb83aff023c90cfc186459603320ad3c622a40b)
Change-Id: Idfd7dfa2284fcea66cf23c4273efda61ee8f7eba
